<BYLINE>Louis L'Amour</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> L'Amour </PERSON>, whose Old West novels about gunfighters, lawmen and drifters drew on his colorful past as a gold prospector, roustabout and jack-of-all-trades, died Friday of lung cancer. He was 80. He wrote 101 books, nearly all of them Westerns, including `` Hondo,'' `` How the West Was Won,'' `` The Iron Marshal,'' `` The Quick and the Dead,'' `` <PERSON> Sackett </PERSON>'s Land,'' and `` Ride the Dark Trail.'' Nearly 200 million copies of L'Amour's books were printed; his works were translated into 20 languages, according to his publisher, <ORGANIZATION> Bantam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Books </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> L'Amour </PERSON> left home in <LOCATION> Jamestown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.D. </LOCATION>, when he was 15, working as prize fighter, deckhand, longshoreman, lumberjack, gold prospector, coal miner, circus roustabout, fruit picker, elephant handler and amateur archaeologist. He became a prolific contributor in the 1940s and 1950s to pulp magazines and his first novel, `` Hondo,'' was published in 1953. It was followed by 85 more, along with 14 short story collections and one non-fiction book. In 1984, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> presented L'Amour with the Presidential Medal of Freedom. <PERSON> L'Amour </PERSON> is survived by his wife <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON>, and a son and daughter.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Robert Stewart</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST LAFAYETTE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, retired <ORGANIZATION> Purdue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> treasurer and executive who administered billions of dollars in GI <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> veterans benefits, died Friday in <LOCATION> Vero </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla </LOCATION>. He was 92. <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>'s 36 years with <ORGANIZATION> Purdue </ORGANIZATION> began in 1925 as its controller. In 1945 he was named vice president and treasurer, a post he held until his retirement in 1961. After World War II, as administrator of <ORGANIZATION> Veteran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vocational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rehabilitation </ORGANIZATION>, Education and Training, <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> coordinated $ 14.5 billion in G.I. Bill benefits for 8 million veterans. He successfully fought President <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Truman </PERSON>'s request that the Veterans Administration examine all textbooks used by veterans to make sure they did not support communist doctrine. Born in <LOCATION> Duluth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> graduated from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION>, earned his doctorate from <ORGANIZATION> Butler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and taught in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>. He was business manager of <ORGANIZATION> Albion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> before coming to <ORGANIZATION> Purdue </ORGANIZATION>. Survivors include his wife, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Josephine Branigin</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST LAFAYETTE , Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Josephine </PERSON> <PERSON> Mardis </PERSON> <PERSON> Branigin </PERSON>, widow of former Gov. <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Branigin </PERSON>, died Saturday at age 80. She was born Feb. 4, 1908, in <LOCATION> Shelbyville </LOCATION> and graduated cum laude from <LOCATION> Franklin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> College </LOCATION>, where she majored in mathematics and biology, in 1929. In 1929 she married <PERSON> Branigin </PERSON>, who served as <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>'s 42nd governor from 1965 to 1968. A retired <LOCATION> Lafayette </LOCATION> attorney, he died Nov. 19, 1975. She is survived by her son, <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Branigin </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, seven grandchildren; and two great-grandchildren.
