<BYLINE>Bill Clark</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WATERVILLE, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, a former schoolteacher who became one of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>'s most widely read newspaper columnists, died Sunday after a brief illness. He was 74. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>'s columns for the editorial pages of <ORGANIZATION> Guy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> newspapers embraced traditional values, often featuring the fictional town of <LOCATION> Cedar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and country characters dispensing folksy wisdom. A native of <LOCATION> Schenectady </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> graduated from <ORGANIZATION> Colby </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> and obtained an education degree from <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. He taught in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> state </LOCATION>, where he became a school principal in <LOCATION> Greenbush </LOCATION>. After serving with the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> during World War II, he built log cabins around <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> George </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, area and operated a sawmill before moving to <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION>. He taught speech and composition at <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> and writing at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maine </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>. His column, `` Logrolling,'' first appeared in the fall of 1956. He is survived by his wife, the former <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, and two sons.
