<HEAD>China's Presence In Hong Kong Is Everywhere _ And Expanding</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 High above <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s imposing skyline, the final girders are swinging into place atop the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION>'s striking prism-shaped building The 70-story glass-and-steel building, to be the local headquarters of mainland <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s official bank, is a none-too-subtle symbol of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s unrivaled influence and growing activity in this British colony which reverts to Chinese sovereignty in 1997. Communist <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s soaring presence is a result of market-oriented economic reforms championed by <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and the part of the agreement with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> that says <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> can keep its capitalist system for 50 years after 1997. Chinese officials of various ranks are invading <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> for a crash course in capitalism and to secure money-making deals. The big Chinese companies are wheeling and dealing in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s high-flying property market, investing in major construction projects and even buying large blocks of local stock Chinese diplomats are busy too. <PERSON> Xu </PERSON> <PERSON> Jiatun </PERSON>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s top diplomat in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, shows up at pop concerts and cocktail parties. He heads the local branch of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> but is viewed by many as the colony's shadow <PERSON> Xu </PERSON>'s main task is to promote stability and prosperity in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, and he is full of kind words for its capitalist society. `` We have some comrades who always fear capitalism, but in fact they do n't understand that the modern capitalist system is a great creation of human civilization,'' he has told reporters. No official figures are available to show how many China-backed companies are in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, but estimates run into the thousands. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is widely regarded as the largest foreign investor in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, with estimates ranging from $ 6 billion to $ 8 billion. The investments include department stores, factories, supermarkets and real estate. Much of the activity is financed by the 14-member <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> group, which saw profits rise by 30 percent to 60 percent in 1987, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> financial research firm. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s property purchases in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> totaled about $ 1 billion last year, exceeded only by Japanese and local investors, according to <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Kwan </PERSON> of <PERSON> Chesterton </PERSON> <PERSON> Petty </PERSON>, an international property consulting company. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> snatched up hotels, office buildings and residential high-rises. `` They have to support the political confidence of people'' in the years before 1997, <PERSON> Kwan </PERSON> said, noting that the injection of Chinese capital creates demand and raises real estate prices. Some deals reflect the need for more space by expanding Chinese companies while other deals are strictly to make money. <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, for example, bought an office building near the central business district for about $ 45 million in May 1987 and then sold it to Japanese interests five months later for a 35 percent profit, according to <PERSON> Chesterton </PERSON> <PERSON> Petty </PERSON>. Other Chinese moves that have turned heads in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> include: _ Bailouts of financially troubled <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> banks and a pledge by the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> of the equivalent in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> dollars of $ 128 million to save the colony's teetering futures exchange after the global stock market crash in October _ The purchase by <ORGANIZATION> CITIC </ORGANIZATION>, which is <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s premier international investment company, of 12.5 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Cathay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, the territory's profitable flag carrier _ Participation of three Chinese companies in three competing consortia bidding for a multimillion-dollar tunnel project through the suburban New Territories Matching <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s flurry of economic activity in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> has been its expanded political work. From the <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> headquarters across the street from the <LOCATION> Happy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> race track, a staff of several hundred stay in touch with nearly every sector of society. <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s Chinese-language Wide Angle magazine reported that the news agency has separate departments responsible for keeping in touch with the <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> government, students, grass-root organizations and the colony's elite. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Y.S </PERSON>. <PERSON> Cheng </PERSON>, a political science lecturer at <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kong </ORGANIZATION>, says <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s plan to win over local residents is `` a longtime process of befriending us, of co-opting us, so when the Chinese come -LRB- in 1997 -RRB- there's a very good chance of us being immobilized or at least neutralized.'' One group that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has successfully cultivated is the power elite, who believe toeing the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> line is the best way to keep their businesses healthy after 1997. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> also can count on several local organizations to support its policies here. For example, the <ORGANIZATION> Hong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unions </ORGANIZATION>, which represents about 170,000 workers, mobilized its members last year to support <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s opposition to general legislative elections in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> this year. This, along with the colonial government's decision to delay elections until 1991, has led some local activists to believe <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> already is calling the shots in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
