<HEAD>Ringling Elephants Arrive For Circus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ending a trans-Pacific boat ride, 16 bleary-eyed performing pachyderms were greeted at a <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> pier by confetti-tossing Shinto priests. Cranes at <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> unloaded the <LOCATION> Ringling </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bros. </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Barnum </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Bailey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circus </ORGANIZATION> performers on Sunday from a cargo ship that left <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. June 1 The elephants, whose weight ranges up to 14,000 pounds, dutifully lined up for photographers. One youngster executed a polite bow. A pair of Shinto priests in ceremonial caps and robes waved twigs at the pachyderms and threw confetti across their trunks, a slight departure from traditional purification rites. The ritual also bestowed hopes for success and safety for the circus' 15-week tour of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Ringling's lions, horses, camels, llamas and chimpanzees arrived earlier to meet quarantine requirements. A circus official said humans and elephants were the only animals Japanese authorities exempted. The elephants continue on to the northern city of <LOCATION> Sapporo </LOCATION>, where the American circus opens its first overseas tour on July 1.
