<HEAD>China Says Jiang Qing Still in Prison, Not In Villa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Qing </PERSON>, the ailing widow of the late Communist Chinese leader <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON> and a key figure in the tumultuous Cultural Revolution, is still in prison and not living in a villa, an official Chinese report said. The <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, in a dispatch published in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> newspapers on Sunday, said a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> had denied unconfirmed press reports that the 74-year-old <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> was released from jail, where she is serving a life sentence, and lives with her daughter in a villa in a <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> suburb. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> is receiving special medical care in jail, the <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> reported. Chinese officials said earlier this year that <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> was suffering from an unidentified `` geriatric disease.'' Recent unconfirmed reports have said she is suffering from throat cancer but had refused treatment because it would leave her voiceless. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> was a member of the notorious `` Gang of Four,'' who were accused of ordering illegal arrests during the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution and trying to seize power in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> after <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> died in 1976. Members of the gang were convicted in 1981 and <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> was sentenced to death, but the sentence was commuted to life imprisonment in 1983.
