<HEAD>`Here, Puli. Here, Boy. Puli? PULI?'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SE1 of June 12</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEDINA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Puli </LOCATION> is a well-behaved Hungarian sheepdog that spends most of his time lying in front of a fireplace, never jumps on the furniture and never makes any noise. <LOCATION> Puli </LOCATION> has been dead four years. But his owners, <PERSON> Suzanne </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rob </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleming </PERSON>, continue to enjoy their preserved dog. `` It's sort of like <LOCATION> Puli </LOCATION> is still alive because of all the laughs he gets,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Fleming </PERSON> said. The Flemings once left the fluffy white dog in the back seat of their car while they went sailing. Upon returning, they asked a friend to let the dog out. `` <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> kept whistling, ` Come here, boy,' took a closer look and said, ` Uh, <PERSON> Rob </PERSON>, I think you might have left your dog in the car too long. He's not moving.' We were in tears we were laughing so hard,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Fleming </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Flemings </ORGANIZATION>' teen-age daughter had a different reaction when she learned her parents had decided to have the family pet freeze-dried instead of buried. The dog was diagnosed with spinal cancer and the <ORGANIZATION> Flemings </ORGANIZATION> had him put to sleep in 1984. Mrs. <PERSON> Fleming </PERSON> understood her daughter's fury. `` I mean, how do you tell your friends that your parents are having -LRB- the family -RRB- dog freeze-dried?'' she asked. For $ 650 a taxidermist in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, posed the dog lying on its side with head up and looking alert. The dog weighs about 10 pounds and needs only occasional cleaning with acetone. The Flemings say they made the right decision, and enjoy having their dog around the house. `` He was like a child to us,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Fleming </PERSON> said.
