<FIRST>u i PM-MysteriousKabul Bjt   06-13 0792</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mysterious Kabul, Bjt,0817</SECOND>
<HEAD>A City With A Bustling Free Market, Run By Besieged Communists</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When the dust storms come, <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> vanishes from sight behind a white cloud that grittily obscures all sense of what is and is not real. Then the winds die down, and the dust suspended in the air drifts to the ground. The sun breaks through and the city of mud brick houses and 2 million people shimmers back into view. It's a bit like stepping into a magic spell and visiting `` Brigadoon,'' the Scottish Highlands town in the Broadway musical that appears for a day once every hundred years before fading away into the mist again. <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> has that same sense. The distinction between reality and fantasy blurs. The Afghan capital is at once communist and capitalist. The government of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Afghanistan </ORGANIZATION> is one of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s most successful attempts to impose communist rule on a Moslem nation. But here, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has entered the fray by supporting and helping arm the anti-communist guerrillas who are fighting Afghan and Soviet soldiers. And in spite of the Soviet-style government, <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> is a capitalist city. Dollars are avidly sought by merchants who sell everything from century-old handwoven Afghan carpets to gaudy lace stockings from <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> sweatshops. <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> is a city full of life and, increasingly, of death. Teen-age girls strive for the latest styles as their tailors stitch government-issue blue cotton into school uniforms patterned on the skirts and jackets shown in European fashion magazines. The markets bustle with more traditionally clad women wearing the `` chadri,'' an all-enveloping veil that descends in pleats from a skullcap with only a coarse mesh panel over the eyes to let the wearer see out. Small boys in pajama-like tunics and pants turn cartwheels in grassy traffic circles, dodging sprays of water from tanker trucks that keep the geraniums blossoming. At night, streets are virtually deserted. The rare motorist is suddenly stopped by an Afghan soldier who emerges from the gloom to wave his rifle and check the traveler's identity. Soviet soldiers have started withdrawing from other cities as part of a pullout the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> says will by Feb. 15 end its eight-year military intervention. But they still surround <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> with a ring of tanks, armored personnel carriers and fortified bunkers. Guerrilla rockets hit <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> several times a week, usually at night. Often they land near <LOCATION> Afghan </LOCATION> and Soviet military posts, but rockets are notoriously inaccurate and many of the casualties are civilians asleep in their homes. One of these victims was carried into a hospital X-ray room a few days ago. The white-haired man lay unconscious on a narrow bed of ropes woven across a wooden frame. His right eye was closed, his left concealed by a bloody bandage. Blood stains covered the shoulders of his brown tunic, and one leg lay at an improbable angle under a red plaid blanket. He had been brought to the hospital, bed and all, by three men wearing turbans, baggy trousers and layers of robes. The old man lived, according to a hospital staff member who said such victims arrive almost every morning. But the staffer refused to give specific numbers, reflecting a reluctance to make statements not authorized by the government. Death is tangible at <LOCATION> Tapa-e-Shuhadan </LOCATION>, `` the Hill of the Martyrs,'' <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>'s cemetery for government troops who have died in the decade of fighting the mujahedeen, or Moslem holy warriors. <PERSON> Tapa-e-Shuhadan </PERSON> is off-limits much of the time, even to mourners, for it is in a military zone. A visit to the hill quickly reveals the reason: <PERSON> Tapa-e-Shuhadan </PERSON> sits atop a huge ammunition dump, evident from the concrete doorways and little ventilation chimneys built into the slopes below the graves. The members of the Peace, <ORGANIZATION> Solidarity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Friendship </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> who escort foreign visitors to the cemtery were at a loss to say how many men are buried there. But a rough reckoning, achieved by counting graves in one quadrant and extrapolating, made 10,000 seem a conservative estimate. These escorted visits add to the blurring of reality and unreality in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. But there are other encounters that seem genuine, like the one with a man in a crocheted white skullcap who declared himself a `` mujahed,'' one of those seeking to oust the government. He spat on the ground to express his contempt for the Afghan government, communism and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Speaking in Arabic he said he had learned from the Koran, Islam's holy book, and from three pilgrimmages to <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> _ one of the countries arming the mujahedeen, he said: `` God willing, the brotherhood of Moslems will see victory in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>.''
</TEXT>
