<FIRST>u i PM-AIDS-Children     06-13 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS-Children,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Raises IQ Of AIDS-afflicted Children, Report Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-AIDS Conference, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A drug widely used to treat adults with AIDS appears to dramatically reverse the devastating effects of the disease on the brains of children, new research shows. The AIDS virus frequently robs young victims of their ability to talk and walk and lowers their intelligence. The latest research shows that the drug AZT seems to bring back children's speech as well as other functions controlled by the brain. `` Functional ability returned to normal in many kids,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Pizzo </PERSON>, who directed the study at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. His research was presented Sunday at the opening of the Fourth International Conference on AIDS. AZT, also known as zidovudine or Retrovir, is the only medicine routinely used to suppress the AIDS virus, called HIV. In adults, it can slow the progression of Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome but does not cure it. <PERSON> Pizzo </PERSON>'s findings were made unexpectedly during the testing of a portable pump to administer the drug to children. He found that among other changes, the youngsters' IQ scores rose about 15 points after they got the medicine. `` Everybody who looks at this data has to get excited,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoth </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Allergy </ORGANIZATION> and Infectious Diseases. `` We are all nervous by small numbers -LRB- of patients studied -RRB-, but the data itself is very exciting.'' Dr. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> also cautioned that the preliminary study did not include a comparison group. `` It's intriguing,'' he said of the results. `` I would have liked to have seen a control group who were not treated.'' <PERSON> Pizzo </PERSON> tested AZT on 21 AIDS-infected children who ranged in age from 14 months to 12 years. About two-thirds got the virus from blood products, while the rest were infected by their mothers before birth. <PERSON> Pizzo </PERSON> said that 62 percent of the patients had suffered clear neurological damage from the virus, and `` in every case they were improved'' after taking AZT. The IQs of those who had obvious brain impairment rose from about 70 to 85. Among those who were judged to be mentally normal when the study began, the IQs improved from about 95 to 105, suggesting that they had probably already suffered subtle mental injury from the infection. <PERSON> Pizzo </PERSON> said the youngsters' continued to improve steadily nine months after the treatment started. Brain scans also showed that missing tissue seemed to be restored in the infected youngsters' brains. <PERSON> Pizzo </PERSON> speculated that cells that had been shrunken by the virus were restored to their normal size. He cautioned that further study will be necessary to learn how long the improvement lasts and whether the children eventually worsen again. In a separate study, Dr. <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilfert </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Durham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, described a preliminary three-month study of the drug's safety in children. She said the work shows that youngsters tolerate the treatment well, and while it's too soon to draw firm conclusions, `` our feeling is that the number of opportunistic infections is substantially reduced.'' Research by Dr. <PERSON> Maxime </PERSON> <PERSON> Seligmann </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Hopital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Saint-Louis </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> suggests that combining AZT with the herpes drug acyclovir significantly improves its effectiveness in people with AIDS. In four months of testing on 130 patients, there were 25 deaths among patients who got AZT alone, compared with 11 among people who got both drugs. `` These preliminary data suggest that acyclovir may have additional benefit without additional toxicity in patients with full-blown AIDS,'' <PERSON> Seligmann </PERSON> said.
