<SECOND>PM-Blair House, Bjt,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>After A $13 Million Facelift, Blair House Now Fit For A King</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The president's guest house is meant to be fit for a king, but when explosive gas leaked in and a chandelier crashed onto the bed where visiting heads of state sleep, some work was clearly in order. Six years and $ 13 million later, <ORGANIZATION> Blair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> is now a `` guest house worthy of this great nation,'' says Ambassador <PERSON> Selwa </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>, the chief of protocol, who oversaw the restoration. <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> could n't stay there last December for his summit with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> because the house was closed for repairs. But should he return this year he would find a new wing, renovated kitchen, plumbing, fire and safety systems, new electrical heating and air conditioning. Not a palace, perhaps, but not the dilapidated antique it was in June 1982. Then the house was judged uninhabitable after gas leaked into the boiler room and a chandelier fell on the bed, fortunately then unoccupied. `` We all realized that the house was in very bad shape. All you had to do was look at it,'' says Mrs. <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>. `` It had a veneer of looking all right because it had a certain warmth and all of that. But the minute you started looking, the rugs were threadbare, the steps were sagging. The plumbing was unbelievable. The kitchens were like kitchens at the turn of the century.'' <ORGANIZATION> Blair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> actually predates the turn of the century, and it is an architectural gem rich in history. It consists of four connecting buildings across from the White House on <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION> and around the corner on Jackson Place. The original house dates from 1824 and was long owned by <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Preston </PERSON> <PERSON> Blair </PERSON>, a member of the powerful, intimate group around President <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> that was called the `` kitchen cabinet.'' Later, the house was a meeting place for leaders on both sides of the conflict that became the Civil War. In a small room to the right of the front door, Col. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> was offered the command of the Union Armies and declined in favor of his native Commonwealth of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. President <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> approved the acquisition of the house in 1942, saying the government needed it `` for the entertainment of distinguished visitors.'' On Nov. 1, 1950, an assassination attempt was made on President <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> Blair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> by two Puerto Rican nationalists who attempted to force their way in. The attempt failed, and one of the nationalists was killed. <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Coffelt </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> guard, died in preventing the assailants from gaining entrance, and a plaque outside the house commemorates his heroism. In more recent times, columnist <PERSON> Diana </PERSON> <PERSON> McLellan </PERSON> got into hot water in 1981 when, writing her column for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, she carried an item that then-President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> had `` bugged'' Blair House where President-elect <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was staying before the inaugural. The Post retracted the item after <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> threatened to sue for libel. When the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> decided in 1982 that <ORGANIZATION> Blair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> was so dilapidated it was dangerous, the agency said millions of dollars were needed to repair the structure. `` The alternative was to tear it down. There was nothing in between,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> appropriated $ 8.6 million, and another $ 4.8 million was raised from private sources to pay for the project. Mrs. <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> hopes to have more than $ 1 million left for a fund to maintain the house. There has been little skimping in the refurbishing. The collection of antiques has been expanded, many of them donated along with china, silver and fabrics. The room where visiting heads of state receive the press is an uncommonly elegant pressroom with its two fireplaces, blue damask upholstery, red serabend rugs and view of the White House across <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sees the house as one of its diplomatic assets. Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> has said the `` feelings of being truly welcome, which staying at the presidential guest house foster, can tip the balance in our favor with many nations where personal relationships are vitally important.'' `` When people feel well-treated and warmly treated, this makes it much easier,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> says. She believes the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people can be proud of the house, which she says is neither ostentatious nor `` plebian.'' `` They do n't want pretensions because the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people are n't that way This house sort of straddles a very nice line. It's not too grand, but it has elegance,'' she says. `` It's really just the right degree of grandness.''
