<HEAD>Sharp Temblor Hits; Preliminary Estimate 5.3</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `The U.S. ...'' to UPDATE with 5.3 Richter
reading, epicenter near 19884 quake; SUBS 8th graf, ``It was ...'
to include that meteorologist is life-long resident of the area.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ALUM ROCK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A strong earthquake startled residents over a 350-mile expanse of Northern and <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> on Sunday night, but authorities said there were no immediate reports of serious damage or injuries. The quake hit at 6:45 p.m. and had a magnitude of 5.1 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale, said a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seismographic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stations </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>. Its epicenter was on the <LOCATION> Calaveras </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fault </LOCATION> about 10 miles northeast of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Alum </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION>, said spokesman <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Lomax </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Geological Survey in <LOCATION> Menlo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> estimated the temblor at 5.3. Geophysicist <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellsworth </PERSON> said the earthquake's 5-mile-long center was just north of the epicenter of a 6.2 quake in <LOCATION> Morgan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> in 1984, the region's largest temblor in years An earthquake of 5 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale is considered capable of causing substantial damage, but authorities said they had no damage reports worse than a few cracked ceilings and a broken water heater and water pipe in nearby <LOCATION> Milpitas </LOCATION>. `` The whole mountain shook,'' said <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Wong </PERSON>, a maintenance supervisor for the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> atop 2,571-foot <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tamalpais </LOCATION> 10 miles north of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Marin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. Residents as far south as <LOCATION> Bakersfield </LOCATION> and as far north as <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rosa </LOCATION> flooded authorities and media with calls about the quake. Police and sheriff's spokesmen throughout the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> area, the <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Napa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sonoma </LOCATION> counties to the north all said they had felt it but were unaware of any damage. `` It lasted longer than they usually do,'' said <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> sheriff's Deputy <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Dominguez </PERSON>. `` It came all of a sudden and then leveled and rolled off.'' `` It was the strongest quake I've felt here in years,'' said meteorologist <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Pechner </PERSON> of radio station <ORGANIZATION> KNBR </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and a life-long resident of the area. A resident of <LOCATION> Foster </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> on the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> said people ran out into the street after the quake hit. A <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> resident said bottles fell off the shelf in his house and plants were tipped over. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Trevan </PERSON>, a motorist who was driving over the Golden Gate Bridge, said his car `` jumped a little bit'' during the quake. <ORGANIZATION> Bay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rapid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> crews slowed trains to check for damage to the tracks, but found none, officials said. <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> said it had no reports of power outages in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION> area adjacent to the epicenter. The quake was the third reported Sunday in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Mild earthquakes jolted <LOCATION> Napa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Solano </LOCATION> counties in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and the inland area of <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> around <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, but there were no reports of damage or injury. The <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION> quake also was felt in the cities of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Fontana </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Riverside </LOCATION>, about 50 miles east of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. It struck about 2:20 p.m. PDT, was centered about five miles east-southeast of <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, and measured 3.4 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale, said Hall Daily, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pasadena </LOCATION>. The temblor was the second widely felt quake to hit <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> since Friday, when a shaker measuring 5.2 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale hit 40 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and was felt in much of central and southern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Daily said initial data indicated it was unlikely the Sunday quake was related to the one which struck Friday. The Napa-Solano quake which measured 3.3 on the Richter scale, occurred at 2:44 p.m., the Seismographic Stations at <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> reported. The epicenter was near <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berryessa </LOCATION>, about 40 miles north of <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Vacaville </LOCATION> police received dozens of calls from residents who were n't sure what the jolt was, said dispatcher <PERSON> Jamie </PERSON> <PERSON> Weishaar </PERSON>. `` Many of the people were confused because it did n't feel like an earthquake. Some people thought it might have been a sonic boom,'' she said. The <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase in the strenth of the shaking. Thus, a reading of 7.5 reflects an earthquake 10 times stronger than one of 6.5. An earthquake of 3.5 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale can cause slight damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage, 6 severe damage. A 7 reading is a `` major'' earthquake, capable of widespread heavy damage, and 8 is a `` great'' quake, capable of tremendous damage. The <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> earthquake of 1906, which occurred before the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale was devised, has been estimated at 8.3 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale.
