 Tennis balls zoomed like missiles over the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> lawn, causing even President and <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to duck, but it was all for a good cause as some $ 500,000 was raised to combat drug abuse. Celebrities, tennis pros and administration officials gathered Sunday at the White House tennis court for the fourth annual fund-raising event. The president and first lady joined a crowd of several hundred guests and corporate sponsors, watching tennis stars <PERSON> Tracy </PERSON> <PERSON> Austin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Vince </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Patten </PERSON> <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Ralston </PERSON> compete in a match that had no winners _ local sportscaster and master of ceremonies <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Brenner </PERSON> got the score mixed up. The first couple also saw Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Fahrenkopf </PERSON> go down to defeat at the hands of Treasury Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wilhelm </PERSON> <PERSON> Wachtmeister </PERSON>, the ambassador of <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, just back from his round of travels to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, appeared to fall victim to jet lag with his double faults. Old and new <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> hands faced off when current <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> and newsman <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Kondracke </PERSON> opposed former <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERS