<HEAD>Dukakis Has Net Worth Of At Least $500,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who once described himself as a `` man of few wants,'' lives in a duplex he bought 17 years ago for $ 25,000, drives a 5-year-old Dodge, buys his clothes at a bargain basement and generally vacations at the homes of friends or family. Despite his frugal lifestyle _ or perhaps because of it _ the apparent Democratic presidential nominee has a net worth of at least $ 500,000 in property, investments and salary and is the potential beneficiary of about $ 1 million controlled by trusts, according to his financial disclosure forms and statements made by his presidential campaign aides. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Dorsey </PERSON>, the governor's <ORGANIZATION> Statehouse </ORGANIZATION> press secretary, said the <PERSON> Dukakises </PERSON> `` live comfortably,'' but added: `` Nowadays there is n't much time to spend money on anything.'' The last time the Democratic presidential nominee-to-be took a financial risk was 25 years ago when, following the lead of two uncles in <LOCATION> Haverhill </LOCATION> a half century before, he took out two mortgages to buy the six-apartment building he was living in for $ 55,000. The investment proved successful. In 1971, eight years after buying the apartment building in the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Brookline </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> sold off the apartments as condominiums _ one of the first condo conversions in the state _ for a reported $ 26,000 profit. Earlier that year, he and his wife, <PERSON> Kitty </PERSON>, moved out of the apartment building and bought half of a side-by-side brick duplex down the street for $ 25,000. The Dukakises still live in that modest, three-story duplex _ since <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> is one of only three states that does n't provide a governor's residence But as a result of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s inflated real estate climate, the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> home now carries an estimated value of $ 367,400 Like many Americans, the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' home is the governor's single largest investment. Unlike many Americans, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has paid off the mortgage. Indeed, the governor, who refuses to use credit cards, has no reported debts. His only independent stock investment totals less than $ 1,000 in a small Massachusetts-based robotics manufacturer, <ORGANIZATION> Automatix </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which brought him less than $ 100 in income last year, according to his financial disclosure forms. The governor has no vacation homes _ his vacations are usually mixed with family visits to a cousin's home in Ft.. <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, to Mrs. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' sister's home on <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cod </LOCATION> or to her father's summer home in the He has no airplanes, boats or a garage full of cars. The only car owned by the man who likes to ride the subway to work is a 1983 Dodge valued last year at $ 2,750. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, 54, has put his money into long-term investments aimed at retirement or benefiting his three children. After 25 years in state politics, first as a legislator and now as a three-term governor, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has built his state retirement account up to $ 49,494. If the governor has taken out life insurance, his federal and state financial disclosure forms do n't reveal it and his presidential campaign staff wo n't discuss it. He and Mrs. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> have $ 44,610 in various savings, <ORGANIZATION> Individual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retirement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounts </ORGANIZATION> and checking accounts, some of which are considered trusts for his children, the campaign staff said. The governor and his wife reported total income last year of $ 108,957. Virtually all of it was from his $ 85,000-a-year governor's salary and Mrs. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' $ 20,000 as a part-time director of the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partnership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Project </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> and the $ 2,000 she earned as director of a college textbook publisher The <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' interest income amounted to $ 1,445. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> also is the potential beneficiary of money from two $ 1 million trusts set up by his late father, <PERSON> Panos </PERSON>. However, half the money in those trusts is slated to go to <ORGANIZATION> Bates </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' father went to school. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has reported two additional trusts, valued at a total of $ 110,000, which were set up by Mrs. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' late grandmother, <PERSON> Mabel </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, and her father, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickson </PERSON>. But only the governor's wife and children are potential beneficiaries. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has no direct control over or involvement in any of these trusts. It was one of the trusts set up by <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' father that drew attention last year when the governor filed a report with the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> revealing that until 1986 _ when he was running for re-election _ the trust included stocks in companies doing business in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. In 1983, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> vocally supported and signed legislation to divest <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> pension fund stocks with South African ties to protest that country's system of racial segregation. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, before withdrawing as a trustee of the trust last year, told the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, which manages the trust, to divest any South African-tied stocks. Stocks in 10 companies were immediately sold. Today the trust, in which <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' mother, Euterpe, and his campaign chairman, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON>, are trustees, has holdings in 21 companies, including <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, several of the so-called `` Baby Bells'' spawned by the breakup of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. So, could <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> be called a millionaire? `` It's not accurate to say that, no,'' campaign spokesman <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Akey </PERSON> said. `` Potential, yes.'' It was during discussion last year over raising the governor's salary from $ 75,000 to an advisory board's recommendation of $ 125,000 that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> described himself as a `` man of few wants. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who eventually agreed to a $ 10,000 raise in governor's pay, balked at the board's further recommendation for a $ 25,000-a-year housing allowance, saying he could live on almost any salary, `` within reason.
