<HEAD>FBI Urged to Curb Surveillance of US Activists</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Hearing begins 1:30 p.m. EDT; top prospects uncertain</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> should include stringent safeguards against abuse in the guidelines it used to launch a lengthy investigation of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration political opponents, says a former <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> aide. <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> said the bureau's investigation of the <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> in Solidarity with the People in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> from 1983 to 1985 was carried out under `` relatively lenient'' guidelines on foreign counterintelligence and international terrorism. The group opposes <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration policies in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. In prepared congressional testimony, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> said the probe could justifiably have been conducted under another set of guidelines, the `` relatively rigorous set of investigative rules'' governing domestic security and terrorism investigations. Details of the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> investigation of <ORGANIZATION> CISPES </ORGANIZATION> surfaced in February. Internal <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> documents showed that agents investigated nuns, union members and college professors who opposed <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> policy, photographing protesters at peace rallies and recording license plate numbers. The investigation involved nearly all of the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>'s field offices. The more lenient foreign counterintelligence guidelines allowed the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> to conduct a much broader investigation than would have been possible under the domestic investigation guidelines. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> suggested that the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> rework the international terrorism guidelines and apply some of the safeguards against abuse that are contained in the domestic security guidelines. The international guidelines permit investigations of entire organizations. Under the domestic standards, investigations must focus on participants who knowingly act to further criminal objectives. The domestic guidelines also specify that before investigations are opened, the danger to privacy and free expression posed by an investigation must be considered. `` If these standards had been conscientiously applied to the <ORGANIZATION> CISPES </ORGANIZATION> investigation, it seems certain that an ongoing intrusion into legitimate political activity would have ended much sooner,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON>. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON>, the attorney general's special assistant for intelligence during the <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> administration, made his remarks in testimony to be delivered to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on civil and constitutional rights. The investigation of <ORGANIZATION> CISPES </ORGANIZATION> began March 30, 1983, prompted by an informant's claim that members were covertly furnishing money and supplies to the <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, a leftist group seeking to seize power in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. The probe was closed in June 1985 when the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> concluded that the group was involved in political activities protected by the First Amendment and was not participating in international terrorism.
