<HEAD>Extreme Right Party Takes A Shellacking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-France-Election, bjt
^By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The anti-immigration <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> has all but vanished from the legislature in nationwide elections, despite winning a stunning 14 percent of the vote in April's presidential balloting. In National Assembly elections two years ago, 35 members of the far-right party won seats. On Sunday, only one survived. But the Front was ambushed less by voters than by a new winner-take-all polling system. Not only did party leader <PERSON> Jean-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> lose his seat, he also dropped $ 17,300 in a bet with a pollster whose organization predicted <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> would be defeated. <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> called the election `` unfair and undemocratic,'' adding that it was unreasonable for a party that won 4 -LCB- million votes in April to be nearly shut out of the legislature in June. The Socialists, who won the presidency and took control of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> in 1981, made it possible for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> to get into the Assembly when they changed the election law from a winner-take-all majority system to a proportional one. The majority system favors large parties. The proportional system, where seats are allotted on the basis of the percentage of votes won, is better for smaller parties. When the conservatives ousted the Socialists from power in the Assembly in 1986, they immediately voted back the majority system. `` We, unfortunately, predicted victory of the Socialist-Communist left, even though they are in a minority, because of the majority system of election which we fought,'' said <PERSON> Jean-Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Stirbois </PERSON>, secretary-general of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>. `` The election system ... was conceived to eliminate the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>. `` And, on the whole, it achieved its objective, at least in Parliament.'' The National Front, vilified by the other political parties and accused of being racist and xenophobic for its anti-immigration platform, burst onto the political scene in 1984 by winning 11 percent of the vote in elections for a <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. The party won 9.8 percent in 1986 legislative elections, not only entering the assembly for the first time, but surpassing 30 seats, the number needed to form a separate parliamentary political group. <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>'s 14.4 percent performance in the 1988 presidential election was 2 -LCB- points above the most optimistic prediction. Though suffering a serious setback in this election, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> recorded at least one success. It brought traditional rightist parties into a deal for mutual support in several constituencies in recognition of its political strength. <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> claimed this arrangement allowed the right to blunt what otherwise would have been a Socialist landslide. Carrying the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> standard will be only <PERSON> Yann </PERSON> <PERSON> Piat </PERSON>, who won re-election from a <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> district. Mrs. <PERSON> Piat </PERSON>, the wife of a naval officer, celebrated both her victory and her 39th birthday on Sunday. `` I am an ardent defender of a strong <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> but a fierce adversary of uncontrolled immigration,'' she said.
