<HEAD>Dukakis Focuses On Anti-Drug Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democratic nominee-to-be <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> says as president, he would wage a `` real war on drugs'' _ something he says the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has failed to do. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was focusing on drug issues today. He had meetings set with leaders of his state anti-drug program and with members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to discuss national efforts to fight drugs. A day earlier, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> to address the nation's mayors, and was harshly critical of the administration's dealings with <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, who is under indictment on drug charges If elected, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayors </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> on Sunday, he would tell the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> and other agencies: `` Never again, never again are you going to bankroll a drug peddler who's poisoning our society and killing our children.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> also chided <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> for ignoring efforts by Latin American leaders to get <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> to step down. `` They tried to go it alone and they fell flat on their face,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said of administration efforts to oust <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said he would direct more foreign aid to anti-drug efforts, including support for drug-crop eradication and step up protection of officials in drug-producing nations who have `` the guts to join us in this war.'' He said the military should be prepared to assist those efforts. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> outlined a domestic anti-drug effort he said would include tougher drug laws and stiffer fines, property seizures and sentences, along with increased cooperation between federal, state and local law enforcement agencies. He called for expanded drug education for students and teachers, and guaranteed access to drug treatment. `` For us, the stakes are clear,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said in a speech well received by the mayors, a largely Democratic group. `` The war is on.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> did not mention his certain Republican challenger, Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, by name. But he attacked administration anti-drug efforts, in which <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> played a part when he headed an anti-drug task force. `` What we have today is chaos,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said of the administration's anti-drug effort. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> picked up endorsements from more than 500 Democratic mayors and vice mayors. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> held a private gathering with several black mayors who support <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s presidential campaign. Several described the meeting as a positive step toward building black support for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, but added that how he resolves differences with <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> will be a crucial factor. Before leaving for <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> met with leaders of the Church of Latter Day Saints and separately with actor <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Redford </PERSON>.
