<FIRST>r i PM-AIDS-Herpes     06-13 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS-Herpes,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Herpes Virus May Aggravate Devastation Caused By AIDS</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-AIDS-Conference, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A newly discovered herpes virus may cause much of the damage to the immune system in people suffering from the deadly disease AIDS, a researcher says. Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON>, one of the discoverers of the AIDS virus, said Sunday that the herpes virus works in concert with AIDS to attack the white blood cells that orchestrate the body's defenses against disease. He said the herpes virus can knock out the body's immune system more effectively than Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome once the AIDS virus has weakened the body's defense. The herpes virus appears to be harmless or to produce only very mild disease in otherwise normal healthy people, <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> said at the opening session of the <ORGANIZATION> Fourth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> on AIDS in <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION>. `` Most of us in this room have been exposed to and probably infected with this virus'' while showing little or no sign of it, he said. The new herpes virus was discovered by researchers in <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON>'s laboratory in 1986 It was initially called HBLV -LRB- for human B-cell lymphotropic virus -RRB- and is now referred to as HHV-6 -LRB- human herpes virus, type six -RRB-. This sixth human herpes virus, though related, is different from the herpes viruses that cause cold sores and genital infections. One of the principal targets of the AIDS virus is the T4 lymphocyte, a white blood cell that serves as the master orchestrator of the body's immune response to invading organisms. It appears, however, that the AIDS virus only infects a small percentage of T4 cells, yet it kills a very large percentage of them. There are a number of theories to explain how this might happen, but <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> proposed that the new herpes virus might be the answer. In studies in the test tube, the herpes virus is a more effective killer of T4 cells than is the AIDS virus, <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> said. It can activate the dormant AIDS virus, and it is more common in AIDS patients _ and in such high-risk groups as homosexuals and drug abusers _ than it is in the population at large, <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> said. The AIDS virus weakens the immune system allowing HHV-6 to enter, HHV-6 activates the virus and kills cells, producing further loss of immune defenses, and the deadly cycle continues. To prove that, <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> will have to do studies with animals, if he can find animals that are infected both by the AIDS virus and HHV-6, he said.
</TEXT>
