 Three minutes and 2 -RCB- pounds of pink tomatoes later, 10-year-old <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Orton </PERSON> was the newly crowned champion of the annual tomato eating contest at the <LOCATION> Bradley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Pink Tomato Festival. `` I'm hungry. I did n't eat since dinner last night,'' <PERSON> Orton </PERSON> said before chomping and chewing his way past two-time defending champion <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> and two other adults Saturday for the title and the $ 50 prize. <PERSON> Orton </PERSON>, of Hermitage, was the first contestant to take his seat before a heap of tomatoes, and he listened attentively as the referee explained the rules, including the three-minute time limit. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, who won last year by tossing down more than 5 pounds of tomatoes, had been the odds-on favorite to repeat this year. He said before the contest that he did not feel well. He came out slow and finished in a three-way tie for second place with <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Wisener </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dallas </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>. `` I think it messed me up on tomatoes,'' <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, who works in a tomato shed, said of the experience. The youngest contestant, 7-year-old <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Star </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, said he entered because, `` I wanted to get some money and I like eating good tomatoes.'' He paused at intervals during the contest and used his T-shirt to wipe tomato juice from his chin. More than 20,000 people attended this year's festival, which also featured the popular all-tomato luncheon, where every item on the menu except coffee and tea had tomatoes as an ingredient.
