<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Attackers yelled anti-American slogans and hurled firebombs and tear-gas bombs at a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government office in a southern city today, officials said. The attack on the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> office in <LOCATION> Taegu </LOCATION>, 150 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, caused no casualties and only minor damage. The attackers tossed three firebombs and two tear-gas bombs at the office, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials and police said. Three attackers, believed to be students, were seized by police guards who stopped them with tear-gas guns. Up to 10 radicals were involved in the attack, according to news reports. Six windows were broken and the center's sign set on fire in the attack, officials said. The center, which promotes information about the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and organizes cultural events, was briefly evacuated. The attack followed a wave of violent anti-government and anti-U.S. protests during the past two weeks by radical students who have been demanding the overthrow of President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON>'s government and an end to <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>'s alliance with <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Anti-Americanism dominated the protests, with radical students claiming the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> enforces the partition of the divided <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> peninsula </LOCATION> so it can rule the south. The radicals want immediate reunification with the communist north and removal of the 42,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops based in the south under a mutual defense pact. The two Koreas, divided since 1945, are bitter enemies. The north invaded the south in 1950 to launch the Korean War. The radicals, a small but powerful minority on campuses, have failed to attract public support.
