<HEAD>Mylar Tape Sculpture Removed From Aspen Mountain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASPEN, Colo.(AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Six miles of shimmering Mylar tape, described as a sculpture, has been removed from <LOCATION> Aspen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> and wrapped around the entrance to the <LOCATION> Aspen </LOCATION> Art Museum, sponsor of the exhibit. The tape exhibit, named `` Beacon Interrogator,'' was completed last week for an art show entitled `` Sculpture-Aspen 1988.'' When construction began on Thursday, protests started coming in and one resident suggested in a letter to the editor of an <LOCATION> Aspen </LOCATION> newspaper that the town should `` can the glitter or move it to <LOCATION> Vail </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Aspen </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vail </LOCATION> are rival ski spas in the <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rockies </ORGANIZATION>. `` There's always been security in the mountain, white in the winter, brown in the spring, green in the summer,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Drueding </PERSON>, a town zoning official. `` Now I look up there and see something I've known for 15 years and it's changed.'' `` It's surprising to me that people feel as strong as they do about me decorating their mountain,'' said <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> artist <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Lipski </PERSON>, designer of the tape display. `` My guess is that there is some complex sociology underneath that has nothing to do with my piece.'' The tape was removed from the mountain secretly early Saturday and carried to the art museum. It had been scheduled to remain on the mountain through Sept. 25.
