reaction, more reaction from friends and family, TRIMS. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judge today rejected a bid to reopen the trial of the <LOCATION> Sharpeville </LOCATION> Six, and the blacks convicted for a mob murder once again faced hanging unless President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> intervenes. The judge gave the defendants 35 days to appeal to <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> or the chief justice. The president already has turned down an appeal for clemency. In doing so, he spurned an international campaign to spare the six, who were found guilty in the mob killing of a black town councilor. <ORGANIZATION> Pretoria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Willem </PERSON> <PERSON> Human </PERSON>, who presided over the original trial in 1985, rejected an application by defense lawyers to reopen the case to consider allegations that police coerced two state witnesses. The defendants _ five men and a woman _ were convicted of complicity in the 1984 death of black town councilor who was stoned to death and burned during riots provoked by a rent increase. Human, who had granted a stay of execution hours before the six were to hang in March, said today the request to review the case was `` frivolous and absurd.'' But he extended the stay of execution, which would have expired today, until July 19, giving defense attorneys 35 days to appeal once again to <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> and ask Acting Chief Justice <PERSON> P.J </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rabie </PERSON> to overrule the court's decision. However, Human indicated he felt the chief justice would not overturn his decision by telling the lawyers that their only remaining hope lay in petitioning <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> again. Several dozen friends, relatives and diplomats crowded into the courtroom did not react immediately to the reading of the decision, but some broke down and wept in the corridor when attorney <PERSON> Prakesh </PERSON> <PERSON> Diar </PERSON> explained the ruling to them. They then went to <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> prison to visit the six convicts. <PERSON> Diar </PERSON> said, `` It's a bit surprising that he would give a time limit'' on when the chief justice would have to make a decision. `` Our experience when you petition the chief justice -LRB- is that -RRB- it takes many months. He's giving us a deadline for the chief justice to make up his mind. I think I'm losing a little extra hope with the judge's attitude.'' Human said apart from allegations that two witnesses were coerced, there was ample uncontested evidence to implicate all six defendants and he would not extend the stay of execution beyond July 19. <PERSON> Diar </PERSON> said he would try to appeal to the chief justice. But he said the fate of the six was really in <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s hands. `` I hope and I pray that the state president will reconsider his previous decision. This is a politically related case. -LRB- <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s decision -RRB- may be based on political considerations. <PERSON> Diar </PERSON> said he spoke to his clients last week and described them as `` hopeful, but not confident.'' Prosecutors argued during a hearing last week that Human had no jurisdiction to reopen the case because an appeal has been rejected by the country's highest court, the <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. Defense lawyers had said Human could reopen the case if he determined the trial court was defrauded by false evidence obtained through coercion. But Human said today that further questioning of a state witness who recanted part of his incriminating testimony would be `` an exercise in futility.'' The six were granted a stay of execution March 17, one day before they were to hang. Their case has generated controversy in part because they were not convicted of contributing physically to the councilor's death. They were convicted under the doctrine of common purpose, which held them responsible because they actively participated in the mob which killed the councilor. The government has contended that the six have been unfairly portrayed abroad as innocent victims of an unjust law. Authorities say evidence at the trial showed that each played an active part in the killing, through such actions as making firebombs to burn the victim's house and slapping a woman who pleaded for the councilor's life The defendants are <PERSON> Mojalefa </PERSON> <PERSON> Sefatsa </PERSON>, <PERSON> Reid </PERSON> <PERSON> Mokoena </PERSON>, <PERSON> Oupa </PERSON> <PERSON> Diniso </PERSON>, <PERSON> Duma </PERSON> <PERSON> Khumalo </PERSON>, <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Mokhesi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Theresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramashamola </PERSON>, the only woman on Death Row for what activists say is a politically related crime. Through the policy of apartheid, the white minority government has established a racially segregated society and denies the country's 26 million blacks a vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services. Black officials in the government's employ are thus often resented by other blacks.
