<HEAD>Socialists, Short of Majority, Look To Form Coalition</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 20 grafs to UPDATE with final election results
from Sunday, reax from financial markets. Pickup 19th graf pvs,
``In 1986...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market and the franc dropped today after voters denied <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> a legislative majority and created the prospect of an unstable governing coalition. The Socialists emerged from Sunday's second round of voting with the biggest bloc of votes, but must now look to the Communists or the centrists for a coalition partner to form a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> majority. Just a few weeks ago, the Socialists were widely expected to gain an absolute majority. Also, the extreme-right <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> all but vanished from the legislature, winning just one seat against 35 two years ago. Among the casualties was party leader <PERSON> Jean-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>. Some commentators said the political landscape could remain unsettled for weeks or even months. Such uncertainty would be unusual in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, which has known only stable government majorities since <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaulle </PERSON> founded the Fifth Republic in 1958. Share prices declined on the <ORGANIZATION> Paris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> today in reaction to the prospect of instability, retreating an average of more than 2 percent. The franc fell to 3.38 against the Deutsche mark, compared to 3.39 at Friday's closing. `` The market hates a vaccum,'' said one trader at the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> exchange. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>'s premier, <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON>, tried to put the best face on the party's disappointment. `` You have chosen prudently,'' he told voters Sunday night in a television address. `` It will take several days to draw the appropriate conclusions of all these choices.'' However, others were more pessimistic. `` It will be the most subtle and complex situation you could imagine,'' said political commentator <PERSON> Alain </PERSON> <PERSON> Duhamel </PERSON>. The Socialists could put together a majority in the 577-seat <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> either by joining with the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> or by enticing some centrist members of the conservative coalition to change sides. Neither path looked easy. It also was possible that the Socialists would set up a minority government with <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> or someone new as premier. They would then try to win by seeking votes to the left or the right, depending on the issue. The Communists said they would not consider forming a coalition with the Socialists unless <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> reverses his movement toward the center and launches radical new economic policies to fight unemployment and poverty. Centrist leaders said they would not abandon their conservative allies. But they also indicated the time has come for right and left to find a way to work together. Sunday's election filled 575 seats in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>; the final two seats will be determined in <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Polynesia </LOCATION> on June 26. It takes 289 votes to form an absolute majority in the assembly. The Socialists had 276 seats. Just barely behind, the conservative alliance had 271. The conservative Rally for the Republic won 126, the center-right <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> took 129, and smaller rightist parties collected a total of 16. The Communists had 27. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> salvaged one seat. Its leaders said it fell victim to the replacement of a proportional electoral system by a system of majority vote in two rounds, which favors larger parties. The first round was June 5. Sunday's runoffs were in the 453 districts where no candidate won a majority the first time, and voter turnout was estimated at 71 percent. In 1986, the conservatives won control of the legislature and <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> was forced into an uncomfortable `` cohabitation'' with the right. But following <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>'s solid re-election victory May 8 with 54 percent of the vote over then-Premier <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, it was widely expected that the Socialists would win a handy absolute majority in the assembly. But the pre-election polls proved wrong. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> met late Sunday night with <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> but made no immediate public statement. The new <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> is to meet for the first time June 23. After <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> was first elected in May 1981, he called legislative elections and won a clear majority for his Socialists. He named four Communists Cabinet ministers, but they later quit when the government switched to an economic policy of austerity. Recently, <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> said the Socialists should pursue an `` opening'' toward the center, although exactly what he means has been the most-debated question in recent French politics. <PERSON> Georges </PERSON> <PERSON> Marchais </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said his forces would vote for any Socialist proposals `` favorable to popular and national interests,'' but not commit them in advance to backing the government unless <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> changes course. <PERSON> Marchais </PERSON> called for `` a policy of effective struggle against unemployment, poverty and social inequality, an increase in purchasing power, salaries, pensions and welfare payments, a policy of new growth in the economy, a policy of freedom preserving the rights of wage-earners and the independence of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, a policy of peace and disarmament.'' <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>'s policies by now may be closer to those of the centrists. However, the centrists have longstanding ties to their conservative partners that will not be broken easily.
