<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to decide whether the government may use a 19th Century anti-fraud law to impose stiff civil fines on top of criminal penalties assessed for the same offense. The court said it will hear an appeal by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration officials seeking to fine the manager of a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> medical laboratory $ 131,170 for defrauding the government of $ 585 on Medicare bills. The government imposed the penalty against <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Halper </PERSON>, who runs <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Halper </PERSON> was convicted criminally of submitting inflated claims for Medicare reimbursement. He was sentenced to two years in prison and fined $ 5,000. Government officials then also fined him $ 131,170 under the False Claims Act, a civil statute enacted in 1863 to combat fraud against the Union army by Civil War defense contractors. The civil fine was based on $ 2,000 for each of 65 separate charges of overbilling plus $ 1,170 for double the actual loss suffered by the government. The government said <PERSON> Halper </PERSON> billed <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Greater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> at $ 12 per patient for a service that <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> reimburses at $ 3. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sweet </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> originally reduced the civil fine to $ 17,170 and subsequently cut it to $ 1,170 when the government protested the first reduction. Sweet said the stiff fine the government wants `` amounts to a criminal penalty for violations for which <PERSON> Halper </PERSON> has already been punished.'' He said the original fine `` bears no rational relation to the government's loss.'' The judge said the civil fine violated <PERSON> Halper </PERSON>'s double jeopardy protection against being punished twice for the same offense. In the appeal filed today, government lawyers pointed out that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 increased the fines so that offenders now may be penalized from $ 5,000 to $ 10,000 per offense, plus triple the actual government loss. `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> strengthened the government's civil remedies because it determined that more severe sanctions were needed in order to stem the tide of rampant fraud inflicted on the government,'' <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers said. Such a stiff penalty `` is reasonable and well within <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>'s legislative power,'' they said The case is <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Halper </PERSON>, 87-1383.
