<HEAD>World's Most Powerful Atom Smasher Set To Explore Nature's
Mysteries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATAVIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The world's most powerful atom smasher is set to start exploring some of nature's deepest mysteries this week and physicists are thrilled at the prospects for scientific breakthroughs. After nearly 10 years of construction and fine-tuning, the giant collider at the <ORGANIZATION> Fermi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accelerator </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in suburban <LOCATION> Batavia </LOCATION>, west of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, is ready to come on line to smash protons and antiprotons together. `` We have the potential for making more discoveries in high-energy physics than at any other time in history,'' says <ORGANIZATION> Fermi </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Lederman </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Fermilab </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Dease </PERSON> said today that the start-up date is not certain but it is expected to be this week. More than 200 physicists from around the world will be participating in the search for tiny subatomic particles that have so far eluded scientists trying to unravel the basic details of how the universe works. <ORGANIZATION> Fermilab </ORGANIZATION>'s collider has three times the power of its closest competitor, the <ORGANIZATION> CERN </ORGANIZATION> collider in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, and could open the door to new, unexpected scientific discoveries, officials say. `` Now we really get to go into the unknown,'' says <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> physicist <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwitters </PERSON>. `` That's why we're in the business.'' <PERSON> Schwitters </PERSON>, co-director of the $ 40 million Collider Detector Facility, compared the collider to using `` wrecking bars and sledgehammers to try to find the treasure.'' The Fermilab collider whirls protons and antiprotons around in opposite directions on a 4-mile circular track called the Tevatron. The protons and antiprotons travel at a speed close to that of light _ 186,000 miles a second. When they collide, they annihilate in a burst of energy reaching 2 trillion electron volts, equivalent to a temperature of 10,000 trillion degrees. The detector facility traps the traces of particles produced by the collisions.
</TEXT>
