<HEAD>Court Rules in Michigan Police-Rights Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled today that police officers sometimes may chase a person who starts running at the sight of them even though they have no reason to suspect criminal conduct. The court unanimously ruled that <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> prosecutors may use as evidence the drugs dropped by a man who began running when he spotted a police cruiser on a <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> street. Writing for the court, Justice <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> officers' pursuit of <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Mose </PERSON> <PERSON> Chesternut </PERSON> did not amount to a `` seizure'' under the Constitution's Fourth Amendment. The amendment generally requires police to have a warrant or `` probable cause'' to suspect a crime before conducting any search or seizure. The court held in 1980 that a person is seized _ as opposed to arrested _ when, `` in view of all of the circumstances surrounding the incident, a reasonable person would have believed that he was not free to leave.'' Adhering to that principle, <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> said <PERSON> Chesternut </PERSON> `` was not unlawfully seized during the initial police pursuit.'' <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> noted that the police did not sound their cruiser's siren or order Chesternut to halt They merely pursued him as he ran, <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> said. `` While the very presence of a police car driving parallel to a running pedestrian could be somewhat intimidating, this kind of police presence does not, standing alone, constitute a seizure,'' he said. According to court records, <PERSON> Chesternut </PERSON> was standing on a <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> street corner talking to another man a little after midnight on Dec. 19, 1984 when he saw a police cruiser. Police said <PERSON> Chesternut </PERSON> immediately started running away, and was followed by the officers. After turning a corner, and as the cruiser drew alongside of him, <PERSON> Chesternut </PERSON> threw a number of packets to the ground and then stopped. The officers said they picked up the packets, which appeared to contain narcotics, and then arrested <PERSON> Chesternut </PERSON>. He was charged with possessing heroin, codeine and diazapan. A state judge threw out the case, ruling that police lacked a reasonable suspicion to pursue Chesternut and therefore had seized the evidence unlawfully. A state appeals court upheld the dismissal. But today's ruling reinstated the charges against <PERSON> Chesternut </PERSON>. The case is <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> vs. Chesternut, 86-1824.
