<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Postal Service,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rules Postal Service Must Pay Interest to Missouri Letter
Carrier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, ruling that the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> is similar to a private business, said today the service must pay interest on back pay owed to a worker who won a lawsuit charging it with illegal discrimination. By a 5-3 vote, the court ordered interest on back pay for a letter carrier in <LOCATION> Chesterfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, who was fired and later ordered rehired. Justice <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON>, writing for the court, said when the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> was reorganized by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1970 into the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> it became in key respects more like a private enterprise than a government agency. The reorganization launched the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> into the commercial world, specifically allowing it to sue and be sued, <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> said. `` It follows that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is presumed to have waived any otherwise existing immunity of the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> from interest awards,'' he said. The court ordered interest paid to <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Loeffler </PERSON>, who was fired from his job as a letter carrier after 10 years. His superiors said <PERSON> Loeffler </PERSON> violated a rule dealing with the organizing of so-called box-holder mail that is sent to `` current occupant'' at an address and does not carry the resident's name. For a period in 1979 and 1980, letter carriers were not allowed to sort the box-holder mail in separate compartments of their carrying bags before beginning their routes. They were required to leave the third class mail in bundles and sort it out at each point of delivery. <PERSON> Loeffler </PERSON>, who worked in a rural area, openly refused to obey the rule as did two female letter carriers. One of the women was suspended and threatened with dismissal. The other woman was warned but was not otherwise disciplined. <PERSON> Loeffler </PERSON> was fired when he was caught breaking the rule the fourth time. He sued the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> under a 1964 civil rights law banning sex discrimination in employment and a federal judge ruled in his favor. <PERSON> Loeffler </PERSON> was awarded $ 91,871 in back pay and was ordered reinstated. But the 8th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled that <PERSON> Loeffler </PERSON> was not entitled to interest the back pay would have earned from the time he was fired until he won the suit. Such interest generally is authorized for those who win anti-discrimination suits under the 1964 act. The appeals court said the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> was immune from the interest payments because <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had not passed a law specifically eliminating the service's protection against such civil rights suits. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration said today's case could affect hundreds of employment discrimination cases pending against the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. Dissenting from the ruling were Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> and Justices <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>. Justice <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> did not take part in the ruling. The case is <PERSON> Loeffler </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, 86-1431.
</TEXT>
