<HEAD>China Has 20 Million Excess Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Chinese factories and offices have at least 20 million excess workers, and the situation is costing the government billions of dollars each year, the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. The news agency quoted an official in charge of personnel affairs as saying that overstaffing costs the state about $ 16.2 billion a year, equal to half the total revenue the state receives from enterprises each year. He said many employees spend working hours playing cards or watching television. At one 800-person factory in <LOCATION> Shijiazhuang </LOCATION>, northeast <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, employees were found to work only four hours during an eight-hour shift, he said. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, with an urban work force of 120 million, has cited low productivity and surplus workers as major obstacles to its drive to modernize industries and make them more profitable. But the government is also committed to keeping unemployment at the present stated level of 2 percent and has said it must create 30 million new jobs by 1990 just to keep pace with the expanding work force. Factory managers have been given authority to dismiss unproductive workers, but it is very rare for workers to be fired for loafing on the job.
