<HEAD>Presbyterians Consider Nuclear Arms Statement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with subcommittee agreeing to
adopt policy statement on nuclear war. Picks up 8th graf: ``We
Presbyterians ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A subcommittee of the nation's largest Presbyterian body today voted overwhelmingly to recommend adoption of a major policy statement on nuclear war. The revised paper on `` Christian Obedience in a Nuclear Age'' was scheduled to be considered later today by a full committee of the 200th <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> of the Presbyterian Church -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- The subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peacemaking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> ended almost four days of at-times contentious debate with a 15-1 vote to recommend adoption of the statement. The subcommittee revised the original proposal to make it clear Presbyterians considered obedience to government the normal course, and to soften language that now declares nuclear deterrence immoral. The subcommittee adopted a writing team's fine-tuning of the policy to agree with earlier changes in recommendations. Meanwhile, the full assembly today took up some internal issues, including commissioning of missionaries. Other issues remaining for discussion by the denomination's highest body include pornography, abortion and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s treatment of Palestinians in its occupied territories On Sunday, the statement on nuclear war was revised to say a Christian `` normally'' should support the government, and nuclear deterrence is immoral `` as an end in itself.'' The 630 delegates are scheduled to take up the report Tuesday evening, the day before the assembly ends. `` We Presbyterians will study this issue to death, while the rest of the world moves on,'' said subcommittee member <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Reindl </PERSON>, an elder from <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, an elder from <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, however, said the paper, and the five-year process that preceded its writing, had led to much debate in the 3 million-member denomination. If the intent is to make peace, especially within the denomination, Ms. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said, `` then let the people sitting beside me in the pew have a chance to look at this.'' Reservations in the subcommittee centered around fears the paper elevated tax resistance and civil obedience above obedience in the church's eyes and promised financial support to those who engage in resistance. However, the revised paper retains declarations that nuclear war is immoral, and says, `` The policy of nuclear deterrence has been in danger of becoming an end in itself rather than an interim measure of self-defense. Such a policy as an end in itself is not morally defensible. The work for peaceful alternatives needs to be vigorously pursued.'' Supporters of the original paper expected the full committee to restore some of the recommendations, including discussions of corporate support, financial and otherwise, for tax resisters. Other issues awaiting assembly action included a recommendation that the church call for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to end its `` repressive'' occupation of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> and that the church ask the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government to stop aid to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> that subsidizes settlements in the occupied territories. Also Tuesday, commissioners face what is expected to be a hotly contested election for stated clerk, the officer responsible for the operation of the assembly. The Rev. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON>, 60, has been stated clerk or interim co-stated clerk of the denomination since it was formed in 1983 by the reunion of the Northern and Southern branches of the Presbyterian church. Previously, he held the office in the Presbyterian Church -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION> -RRB-, the Southern church, for 10 years.
