<HEAD>Nunn Cautious on Democrat's No. 2 Spot; Party Leaders Mixed on
Candidacy</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: One of a series of occasional stories about vice presidential
prospects.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> overcame his reluctance to talk about the possibility of being <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' running mate, the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> senator gave the interview to a newspaper he is sure the <LOCATION> Massaschusetts </LOCATION> governor reads every day _ The <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION>. Frequently mentioned in speculation about the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> vice presidential nomination, the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> has been cautious in indicating his interest _ but he is interested. His response to the question of whether he would even accept the offer is delicately phrased: `` I probably would not accept,'' he told the <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> earns a spot among possible nominees because some judge him the perfect balance on a ticket with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>: _ A conservative Southerner with the liberal Northeasterner. _ An expert on defense with an expert on domestic policy. _ A senator with a governor. `` The best in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> would be <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>,'' said state party chairman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>. `` He's strong on national defense ... and he's perceived to be very intelligent. Because of <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>'s expertise in defense and foreign policy, former <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Robb </PERSON> and others have even talked of <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> being vice president and secretary of <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION>, an unprecedented double role in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government. `` That would be the only reason that he would want to give up the chairmanship, a major substantive role ... to basically sit around an inquire into the health of both his own president and leaders of other countries,'' <PERSON> Robb </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> carefully encourages that by contrasting his clout in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> with the vice president's role: `` You have tremendous potential power, but you do n't have power ... Unless you had some unusual understanding as to what you're going to be _ which I do n't think would be easy to work out for me or anyone else _ I think there's just a very definite problem there. But there is a long list of reasons cited by critics that <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> should not be on the ticket. In general, positions he has taken have caused consternation among various Democratic groups. Civil rights is at the top of the list, and has become a particularly thorny matter with Democratic runner-up <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> pressuring <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> on the issue every day. `` <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> represents the Old South,'' said <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Ireland </PERSON>, a vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> for Women from <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> voted in 1975 against bringing up the legislation to renew the Voting Rights Act. When the law was up again for a vote in 1982, <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> voted for amendments that critics said would weaken the legal protections. In 1980, he voted to continue a filibuster that killed new federal powers to fight housing discrimination. He voted against an extension of time to ratify the Equal Rights Amendment. He supported a constitutional amendment that would overturn the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision legalizing abortion and leave the matter up to each state. Such criticism irritates <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>. `` I do n't enjoy it. I do n't like it. I do n't want my children to read 10, 15, 20 years from now that <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> was against civil rights. That's just absolutely false,'' he told the newspaper. <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>'s aides say that each of his votes was on the specific matter at hand, and often dealt with procedural considerations. For example, aides said <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> voted against the ERA extension because it would not allow states to withdraw a previous ratification vote. On the fair housing bill, <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> argued he did n't want the federal government being both judge and jury on alleged violators Whether or not <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> would object to <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> on the ticket is not known, but his aides quickly started boosting <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> as an alternative choice when <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>'s name was first mentioned. <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> also has a long record of support for many of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s policies. Congressional Quarterly, an independent magazine, ranked <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> as the most frequent supporter of the president among <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> in 1983 and 1985, never dipping below a 58 percent level in votes on <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> issues. `` He's too conservative for me,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> Executive Director <PERSON> Sigrid </PERSON> <PERSON> Freese </PERSON> of <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>. `` He's more Republican than Democrat.'' And there are a series of specific issues on which <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> disagree. <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> voted for aid to the Contra rebels in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, while <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> says that policy is illegal. <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> voted for the MX