<HEAD>Belgian Extradicted to California Also Held Liable to Lawsuits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 People extradited from foreign countries to face criminal charges here can not avoid defending themselves against related civil lawsuits filed in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> courts, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled today. The justices ruled unanimously against <PERSON> Wilfried </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Cauwenberghe </PERSON>, a Belgian citizen who is trying to avoid having to defend himself against a $ 19 million lawsuit in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. The court said <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Cauwenberghe </PERSON> has no right to appeal, before any trial is held, the authority of a Los Angeles-based federal court to preside over the lawsuit. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Cauwenberghe </PERSON> was sued by another Belgian, <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Biard </PERSON>, who lent $ 1 million to a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> real estate partnership engaged in renovating a <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> townhouse complex. According to court papers, <PERSON> Biard </PERSON> was repaid $ 800,000 of the loan and accused <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Cauwenberghe </PERSON> of fraud. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Cauwenberge </PERSON> also was convicted in federal court in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> of wire fraud and related charges. He was sentenced to time already served in pretrial confinement and was ordered to pay Biard $ 34,501 in restitution. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Cauwenberghe </PERSON> had been arrested while on a trip to <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and was extradited to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. In seeking to have <PERSON> Biard </PERSON>'s civil lawsuit dismissed, <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Cauwenberghe </PERSON> argued that the Belgian courts are a more convenient forum for the civil case, and also that extradited individuals are immune from such suits. A federal judge refused to dismiss the suit and the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> said it was premature for it to hear <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Cauwenberghe </PERSON>'s appeal. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed that any such appeal by <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Cauwenberghe </PERSON> can wait until after the trial is completed. Justice <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, writing for the court, said <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Cauwenberghe </PERSON>'s freedom is not at stake in the case. Van Cauwenberghe can not be imprisoned or required to post bail in a civil suit and, in fact, is not even required to be present at the civil trial. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Cauwenberghe </PERSON>'s right to challenge the outcome of the lawsuit can be vindicated after there is a judgment in the suit, <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> said. The case is <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Cauwenberghe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Biard </PERSON>, 87-336.
