<FIRST>u w BC-ScotusAt-a-Glance     06-13 0850</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Scotus At-a-Glance,830</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions taken Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. VACCINE The court ruled the government may be forced to pay damages when a vaccine it licenses causes the disease it was intended to prevent. By a 9-0 vote, the justices rejected <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration arguments that the government always should be shielded from lawsuit in such cases. The case is <PERSON> Berkowitz </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 87-498. SENTENCING The court agreed to judge the constitutionality of a new sentencing system for people convicted of federal crimes. At issue in the sentencing case is whether the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Sentencing Commission's rules that took effect Nov. 1 may stand or must be thrown out. The validity of the commission itself is at stake, also. By the time the court announces its decision, expected sometime in 1989, thousands of defendants will have to be resentenced _ regardless of which way the court rules. The case is <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Mistretta </PERSON>, 87-1904. POLICE AUTHORITY The court armed police with new authority, ruling that officers sometimes may chase someone who starts running at the sight of them even though they have no reason to suspect criminal conduct. It unanimously ruled that <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> prosecutors may use as evidence the drugs dropped by a man who started running when he spotted a police cruiser on a <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> street. The case is <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> vs. Chesternut, 86-1824. RACIAL DESEGREGATION The court declined to study an unprecedented racial-desegregation case, refusing to free <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, officials from having to integrate city schools and build subsidized housing to overcome decades of discrimination. The court, without comment, left intact rulings that <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> must build subsidized housing in predominantly white sections of the city and create `` magnet'' schools to reduce segregation. The cases are <ORGANIZATION> Yonkers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 87-1632, and <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 87-1686. FRAUD The court agreed to decide whether the government may use a 19th Century anti-fraud law to impose stiff civil fines on top of criminal penalties for the same offense. The court said it will hear an appeal by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration officials seeking to fine the manager of a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> medical laboratory $ 131,170 for defrauding the government of $ 585 on Medicare bills. The case is <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Halper </PERSON>, 87-1383. POSTAL SERVICE _ The court ruled that the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> is similar to a private business and said the service must pay interest on back pay owed to a worker who won a lawsuit charging it with illegal discrimination. By a 5-3 vote, the court ordered interest on back pay for a letter carrier in <LOCATION> Chesterfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, who was fired and later ordered rehired. The case is <PERSON> Loeffler </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, 86-1431. DIRECT MAIL The court barred states from banning all direct mail advertisements sent by lawyers to potential clients. The court, by a 6-3 vote, ruled in a <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> case that states violate free-speech rights when prohibiting lawyers from soliciting business by sending truthful and non-deceptive letters to people they know face particular legal problems. The case is <PERSON> Shapero </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, 87-16. DUPONT-LAROUCHE The court rejected the appeal of a <ORGANIZATION> DuPont </ORGANIZATION> family fortune heir declared mentally incompetent after he loaned $ 212,000 to a group linked to political extremist <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON>. The court, without comment, let stand rulings that control of <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> duPont <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>'s $ 8 million estate properly was taken from him in 1985 under <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s guardianship law. The case is <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, 87-1753. HUMANIST The court turned down the appeal of a philosophy professor denied an opportunity to address <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> about secular humanism during the lawmakers' daily moments of opening prayer. The court, over one dissenting vote, refused to hear arguments that the professor's rights were violated. The case is <PERSON> Kurtz </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, 87-1581. CHILD SUPPORT The court told <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>'s highest court to restudy the case of a teen-ager born out of wedlock who says she should be allowed to seek support payments from her father's estate. The justices said the <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> should review its ruling that a $ 4,600 settlement between <PERSON> Heather </PERSON> <PERSON> Jo </PERSON> <PERSON> Krueger </PERSON>'s parents after she was born bars her from seeking any additional money The case is <PERSON> Gernardt </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, 87-1103. ANTITRUST LAW The court ruled that companies may violate antitrust law when they lobby private organizations that play a prominent role in influencing business legislation. The 7-2 decision upheld a $ 11.4 million jury award against a company accused of `` packing'' a meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> when the organization adopted a safety code for electrical wiring. The case is Allied Tube vs. Indian Head, 87-157. EXTRADITION People extradited from foreign countries to face criminal charges here can not avoid defending themselves against related civil lawsuits filed in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> courts, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled today. The justices ruled unanimously against <PERSON> Wilfried </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Cauwenberghe </PERSON>, a Belgian citizen who is trying to avoid having to defend himself against a $ 19 million lawsuit in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. The case is <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Cauwenberghe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Biard </PERSON>, 87-336.
