er </PERSON> says he hopes to buy back some of the treasures for his museum in this town at the tip of the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Keys </LOCATION>. `` There's been a tremendous amount of paperwork'' since his crew found the <PERSON> Atocha </PERSON>'s treasure, said <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON>, 65, who oversees his non-profit <ORGANIZATION> Mel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fisher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maritime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heritage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> began his search for the Atocha about 1970 The effort was marked by financial troubles and court battles, and <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON>'s oldest son and daughter-in-law were killed when their tugboat capsized during a 1975 search In 1982, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rejected the state of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s bid to keep a quarter of the salvor's haul <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> estimates there are at least another $ 100 million worth of artifacts from the Atocha remaining on the ocean floor. `` 1985 was just the beginning. We're going to be working for years and years. The stuff takes forever,'' says <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McGarry </PERSON>, executive director of the museum, which shares quarters with <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON>'s treasure restoration facility. The museum's $ 10 million displays, gleaned from the Atocha, <PERSON> Margarita </PERSON> and from a British slaving ship found during the quest for Spanish treasure, range from dishes to gold bars to a $ 1.13 million gold necklace studded with diamonds, rubies and pearls. But <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> is n't content to count his Spanish treasure. The former <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> dive-shop operator now dreams of building <ORGANIZATION> Treasure </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION>, a $ 140 million resort and research complex in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>. The government of <LOCATION> Antigua </LOCATION> has agreed to a 99-year lease on its isle of <LOCATION> Barbuda </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> plans to build a 400-unit hotel, a treasure museum, preservation facilities and an underwater restaurant. After a year of exploring the area, his crews have found an unidentified shipwreck and the bones of a British vessel. `` It'll never end,'' said <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON>'s son, <PERSON> Kim </PERSON>, a treasure hunter since age 9 and one of the divers combing the Atocha site. `` I'm going to go out tomorrow and find more stuff for them to clean up.
