Russian Orthodox Church and most other religious groups recognized by Soviet authorities are based in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, making it easier for the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> to control them. Strict laws prohibit religious groups from doing charitable work, require them to be registered with the government and sharply restrict religious education. Officials say the laws are being rewritten to reflect <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s efforts to reform Soviet society. <PERSON> Casaroli </PERSON>, leading a <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> delegation at celebrations of the Russian Orthodox Church's 1,000 th anniversary, carried a letter from <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> <PERSON> Casaroli </PERSON> said the pontiff expressed the desire in his letter for regular contacts with the Soviet government. The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> also expressed in general terms its concern over the naming of bishops and the establishment of a seminary for Ukrainian Catholics. The Ukrainian <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> was forcibly integrated into the Russian Orthodox Church in 1946 by <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> but has survived underground since. It has not been recognized by authorities and therefore is illegal. <PERSON> Casaroli </PERSON> and <PERSON> Willebrands </PERSON> met last Friday with five bishops and priests of the Ukrainian <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. Russian Orthodox Church officials, who are opposed to official recognition of the Ukrainian church, have said they will discuss this with <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> representatives later this month. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Casaroli </PERSON> shook hands in the meeting room in the Council of Ministers building in the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> and then sat down at a table with Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> and interpreters. They did not discuss the letter before reporters, who were present for the first couple of minutes of their meeting. Instead, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> asked if <PERSON> Casaroli </PERSON> had been cold in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. The cardinal said he knew what kind of weather to expect since he had been to the Soviet capital in 1971. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said he had been to <LOCATION> Sicily </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> officials told reporters that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> read a Russian translation of the papal letter during the meeting. Members of the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> delegation, the highest ever to visit the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, will travel to <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> this week for continued celebrations of Christianity's anniversary.
