<HEAD>Study Says 3 of 1,000 Hospital Patients Infected With AIDS Virus</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-AIDS Meeting, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About three of every 1,000 patients at six <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hospitals are infected with the AIDS virus, but it has not spread extensively in the past year, according to a study released Monday. It indicated the infection rate among hospital patients is about five times higher than that among military recruits from the same cities but has not changed over the first 15 months of the study. `` The importance is that there has been a slowing in the rate of new infection,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dondero </PERSON>. `` The stable rate means it is not exploding.'' <PERSON> Dondero </PERSON>, a researcher at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, heads the study program called the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sentinal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Surveillance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>. He said the infection rate seen at the six hospitals, four of them in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, probably is lower than the rate nationwide. If the rate at the hospitals were the same as the national figure, that would mean about 700,000 Americans carry the AIDS virus. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> officially estimates between 1 million and 1.5 million Americans are infected, and <PERSON> Dondero </PERSON> said he believes the true figure `` is closer to 1 million.'' Figures are based on anonymous blood testing of 18,809 hospital patients. Excluded from the tests was anyone who might already have the disease, acquired immune deficiency syndrome, including patients hospitalized for infections or cancer. Many of those tested were in the hospital for accidents, surgery or childbirth. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> plans to expand the program to 40 hospitals across the country. Dr. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Grady </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> state epidemiologist, said the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> study may have missed an increase in the infection rate because it did not sample enough people and did not choose a truly representative sample of the population. `` There is a feeling across the country that the infection rate in gay men is stabilizing and that it is still going up in intravenous drug users,'' he said.
