they had only enough fuel for eight shuttle boosters, enough for four flights. Each set of boosters needs 1.7 million pounds of ammonium perchlorate mixed with its rubber-like fuel. <ORGANIZATION> Kerr-McGee </ORGANIZATION> temporarily halted its production of ammonium perchlorate after a series of thunderous explosions May 4 killed two people, injured 326 and caused an estimated $ 73 million in damage at the <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Production </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Henderson </LOCATION>. After a brief reopening the next week, production was halted again under the threat of lawsuits by state and local officials until an independent safety team could inspect the plant. <ORGANIZATION> Kerr-McGee </ORGANIZATION> agreed, among other things, to ship the chemical in containers less susceptible to heat and shock, and reduce by 50 percent its supply of unfinished ammonium perchlorate. The cause of the <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> blast is still under investigation. Company officials have said the blast may have been caused by a leaking natural gas line, but fire department sources said the most likely cause was a spark that set off ammonium perchlorate. <PERSON> Parrish </PERSON> said he would not speculate on when the department's formal report fixing the cause of the explosions will be finished
