<HEAD>Alaska-Siberia `Friendship Flight' Helps Thaw Icy Relations With
Soviets</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede Anchorage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOME, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> delegation hoping to improve U.S.-Soviet relations and reunite Eskimo families divided by the Cold War took off today on a `` friendship flight'' to the Siberian community of <LOCATION> Provideniya </LOCATION>. The flight, aimed at cracking open a border closed for 40 years, left <LOCATION> Nome </LOCATION> at 11:09 a.m. -LRB- ADT -RRB- for <LOCATION> Provideniya </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said. Dubbed Friendship 1, the plane had left <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION> at 7:55 a.m. for the 1 -LCB- - hour flight to the western <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Nome </LOCATION>, the jumping-off point for the second leg of the trip, a 45-minute flight to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> The flight from <LOCATION> Nome </LOCATION> to the eastern <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> port of <LOCATION> Provideniya </LOCATION> is seen as a big step toward thawing relations between the neighboring regions, once part of the same country before <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> sold <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1867. Eskimos once freely crossed the icy <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> in motorboats and walrus-skin umiaks to trade and visit with relatives. The border was closed in 1948 amid growing Cold War tensions. This month, the Soviets approved today's one-time charter flight to <LOCATION> Provideniya </LOCATION>, after two years of work by Alaskans promoting the idea. Eighty government officials, <PERSON> Eskimos </PERSON> and journalists were booked aboard the <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> plane for the 225-mile flight. <LOCATION> Provideniya </LOCATION> officials planned to entertain the one-day visitors with tours, a banquet and a trip to an outlying native village. The flight is long overdue, says <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Gologergen </PERSON>, 68, one of several Siberian Yupik Eskimos who are making the trip. `` This is the first chance to create peace towards our people and their people,'' he said. `` This way we'll have a chance to find out if the relatives are still alive there someplace and open up a little trade.'' <PERSON> Gologergen </PERSON> said his great grandfather migrated from <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> and kept in touch with relatives there until `` the iron curtain came down.'' The `` friendship flight'' is part of a broader initiative that <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> business leaders, educators, and state officials have launched to improve relations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Those efforts, combined with Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of openness, have started to chip away at long-standing barriers. `` From a symbolic perspective, the trip represents the reopening of an old gateway between <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>,'' said Gov. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON>, delegation leader. `` I'm confident it will lead to better relations between our two countries for years.'' The flight stems from the dream of <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Stimpfle </PERSON>, a real estate agent in <LOCATION> Nome </LOCATION>. When <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s oil recession began two years ago, <PERSON> Stimpfle </PERSON> brainstormed ways to improve the economy of his remote town of 3,700 people. He figured that if the <LOCATION> Alaska-Siberia </LOCATION> border were opened, <LOCATION> Nome </LOCATION> could become an economic and cultural center for both sides of the <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION>. In addition to freer travel by residents, <PERSON> Stimpfle </PERSON> envisioned increas