<HEAD>Presidential Guest Quarters Displayed After $13 Million Makeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials on Monday showed off the $ 13 million renovation of <ORGANIZATION> Blair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, the president's guest quarters where visiting dignitaries can eat in one of three dining rooms, entertain in a cozy library and have their hair styled at a private <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Arden </PERSON> salon. `` It is not too grand, but it has elegance,'' said Chief of Protocol <PERSON> Selwa </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>, who oversaw the restoration. `` It is a guest house worthy of this great nation.'' Manager <PERSON> Benedicte </PERSON> <PERSON> Valentiner </PERSON> said she does n't expect guests for another six weeks because work is only 90 percent complete. The chef, for instance, needs to a proper gas range for cooking. The first official visitor has not been named. <ORGANIZATION> Blair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, a 115-room complex consisting of four connected townhouses on <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION> across from the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, was shut down in 1982 after a malfunctioning gas valve leaked explosive natural gas during one dignitary's stay. In 1985, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> allocated $ 8.6 million for a complete overhaul that included new electrical heating, plumbing and air conditioning systems, roof repairs, installation of fire and safety systems and improved security. The rest of the money _ more than $ 5 million _ was raised privately for refurbishing the interior of the four-story house. Furniture is in the Anglo-American style of 18th and 19th centuries with lots of overstuffed chairs and couches, Oriental rugs and hand-painted wallpaper. `` We wanted it to be soft and light,'' said decorator <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON>, who shared the project with <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Buatta </PERSON>. That was no small feat because heavy curtains will be drawn to keep `` the local <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION> terrorist from looking in the windows,'' he said. Rooms that formerly had dingy white walls were painted a variety of bright colors: salmon, blue, shades of yellow, to name a few. Light streams through the back windows that face an interior garden. Chiefs of state invited by the president to use <ORGANIZATION> Blair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> will sleep in a double canopy bed in a private room, part of a suite that includes another bedroom for a spouse, a sitting room and three bathrooms, one of which has a European bidet. If the leader feels cramped by an 18th century bed, the Blair House staff can arrange for a king-size bed to be installed. `` We will do anything to make them happy,'' said the multi-lingual <PERSON> Valentiner </PERSON>, who will stay on premises to supervise the staff of 13 during a an official visit. The most number of people <ORGANIZATION> Blair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> can accomodate is 27 _ 19 guests and eight staff members. All stay free of charge. If the leader wants see people, he or she can attend to business in a book-lined libary, which <PERSON> Hampton </PERSON> tried to give a masculine feel by using rich brown tones. For news conferences, heads of state have the use of a high-ceilinged room with two fireplaces. Since dignitaries often bring family members, <ORGANIZATION> Blair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> has a private <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Arden </PERSON> studio with professional hair styling equipment. The original house, built in 1824, is rich in history. After the original owner's death it was sold to <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Preston </PERSON> <PERSON> Blair </PERSON>, an intimate of President <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. Before the outbreak of the Civil War, Col. <PERSON> Robert </PERS