<HEAD>Betsy Ross' Descendant Places Wreath</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOY GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Smiling grade school students Monday helped a descendant of legendary seamstress <PERSON> Betsy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> place a wreath at her tomb on the eve of Flag Day. <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Norristown </LOCATION> placed the wreath with the assistance of <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Amend </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>, both 11 amd from <LOCATION> Cranford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>. About 100 people gathered around Mrs. <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>' gravesite in the Atwater Kent Park for the ceremony Amend and <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> were among 62 fifth-graders who attended the ceremony. Mrs. <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, according to some historical accounts, created the first official <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flag, sewing a flag with bars and 13 five-pointed stars. The story goes that a special committee headed by <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> visited Mrs. <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> in June 1776 and asked her to sew a flag based on their rough design. Mrs. <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> was the official flagmaker for the <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. But the story of the first stars and stripes has never been authenticated. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, an administrator at <ORGANIZATION> Bryn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mawr </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, plays saxophone in a big band, and says he is not a practicing Quaker; nor does he belong to any organizations such as the Sons of the American Revolution. But he said he admires his great-great-great-grandmother, who died in 1836, because she was a rebel. `` I do this because <PERSON> Betsy </PERSON> was a pretty cool old girl,'' <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said. `` She was no shrinking violet.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, born <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Griscom </PERSON> to Quaker parents on Jan. 1, 1752, broke with the Quaker tradition of pacifism to support the Revolutionary War, he said. The ceremony Monday was preparatory to the city's Flag Day ceremonies on Tuesday, which commemorates the day <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> officially adopted the flag in 1777.
