<HEAD>Profits of Manufacturers Jump 43 Percent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts new 4th graf, ``The combination,'' to further explain
increase in profits per dollar of sales</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Manufacturing corporations' after-tax profits averaged 6.3 cents per dollar of sales in the first three months of the year, up a sharp 43 percent from the fourth quarter, the government reported Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers' after-tax profits totaled a seasonally adjusted $ 39.4 billion in the first quarter, compared with $ 27.4 billion in the fourth quarter, when profits averaged 4.4 cents per dollar of sales. After-tax profits totaled $ 36.9 billion, a 41.3 percent rise from the fourth-quarter total of $ 26.1 billion in profits. Sales climbed a smaller 2.1 percent in the first quarter to $ 629.1 billion from $ 616.2 billion in the fourth quarter. The combination of rising profits and higher sales boosted the level of profits to 6.3 cents per dollar of sales, an increase of 43 percent over the fourth - quarter performance of 4.4 cents The government said the profit improvement occurred in part because petroleum and chemical companies took large write-offs against profits in the fourth quarter, depressing earnings during that period. Manufacturers of primary metals, electrical machinery and transportation equipment all enjoyed profit gains of more than 30 percent in the first quarter from the final quarter of 1987. Compared with a year earlier, companies reporting profit increases of 50 percent or more were food, paper, printing, petroleum, primary metals, fabricated metals, machinery and instruments.
