<HEAD>Island-Hopping Flight Aims To Break Cold War Barriers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be topped with detail after landing in Provideniya,
U.S.S.R</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOME, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 jet crossed the ice-clogged <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> on Monday in a short but historic flight aimed at bridging 40 years of wariness and distrust between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The one-time charter `` friendship flight'' to the eastern <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> port of <LOCATION> Provideniya </LOCATION> from the western <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Nome </LOCATION> was seen as a tentative first step in thawing relations and reuniting Eskimo families split when the Iron Curtain slammed shut during the Cold War in 1948. The border between <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> was closed first by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and then by the Soviets. Monday's 40-minute flight was approved by the Soviets with little notice earlier this month after two years of work by Alaskans promoting the idea. Eighty government officials, <PERSON> Eskimos </PERSON> and journalists were booked aboard the jet making the 225-mile flight. It left <LOCATION> Nome </LOCATION> shortly after 3 p.m. EDT. <LOCATION> Provideniya </LOCATION> officials planned to entertain the visitors with tours, a banquet and a trip to an outlying native village. The flight is part of a broader effort being mounted by <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> business leaders, educators, and state officials to improve the state's relations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The flight was the dream of <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Stimpfle </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Nome </LOCATION> real estate agent seeking ways to improve <LOCATION> Nome </LOCATION>'s economy. He envisions <LOCATION> Nome </LOCATION> as an economic and cultural center for both sides of the <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> is seeking permission to follow the one-time charter with twice-weekly tourist excursions between <LOCATION> Nome </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Provideniya </LOCATION>. While peaceful interactions begin to flourish, military interest in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> also runs high. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has increased its emphasis on a strong defense in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> fighter jets last year intercepted a record number of Soviet military aircraft off <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s coasts.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Editors: <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Foster </PERSON> is the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>'s regional correspondent covering the Northwest.
</TEXT>
