<HEAD>White House Shrugs Of Reported North Proposal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf to expand Fitzwater quote</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The White House on Monday shrugged off a new book that says former presidential aide <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> proposed using hostage negotiator <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Waite </PERSON> in an attempt to set up <LOCATION> Libyan </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Moammar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON> for assassination. `` We do n't look into <PERSON> Ollie </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> stories,'' said presidential spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>. `` That's history, and world leaders know it. It's a book about <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>. What do we care?'' He called the book's narration about the alleged North episode a `` cockamamie story.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said events involving <PERSON> North </PERSON>, a former staff member of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, were `` a long time ago. I do n't know what he did.'' North was fired in November, 1986, after the discovery of an alleged diversion of profits from the secret <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> arms sales to the Contra rebels in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. North and three other defendants face trial felony conspiracy charges. A newly published book by <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> correspondent <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> and Wall Street Journal national security correspondent <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Walcott </PERSON> said <PERSON> North </PERSON> proposed asking <PERSON> Waite </PERSON> to go to <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION> to meet with <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON>. <PERSON> Waite </PERSON> would ask <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON>'s help in freeing the American hostages in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and then depart, leaving the <LOCATION> Libyan </LOCATION> leader to spend the night at his compound _ where he could be the target of an assassination attempt, according to the book, entitled `` Best Laid Plans.'' The book said <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s plan was quickly rejected.
