CORRECT name of organization to Cuban-American National Foundation.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> promised a group of Cuban-Americans Monday that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government will make `` no accommodations'' with <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>'s communist government. Speaking at a ceremony at which the administration announced agreement with a private foundation on a plan to resettle some 4,000 Latin American refugees, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said `` we have isolated him so effectively, both diplomatically and politically,'' that it would be foolhardy to make concessions in the interest of better relations. `` There will be no diplomatic or political agreements that will prolong the suffering'' of Cubans under <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>'s Marxist dictatorship, he said, adding that <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>'s rule has proved `` calamitous for the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hemisphere </LOCATION>.'' `` There have been no accommodations made with <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>'s corrupt communist government by this administration and, if I may inject a partisan point, I guarantee you there will be no accommodations,'' if he is elected president, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` Freedom for <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> is not a bargaining chip at all,'' he said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also said he would work hard to make TV Marti successful in bringing news of the outside world to Cubans on the mainland, as he said <PERSON> Radio </PERSON> <PERSON> Marti </PERSON> has succeeded in doing. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> and immigration commissioner <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> took part in ceremonies with representatives of the <ORGANIZATION> Cuban-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, a private organization that has agreed to take on the project of helping to resettle some 4,000 Latin Americans in this country. The administration had been pushing for such a program, but was unwilling to have it paid for out of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>. The foundation has volunteered to carry on the work at its own expense, with donations.
