<SECOND>AM-Phobias-Navy Death,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Needs Better Recruit Screening for Phobias, Congressman Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tragedies like the death of a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> recruit during a training program could be avoided if the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> did a better job of screening recruits for potential mental health problems, Rep. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Bilirakis </PERSON> said Monday. `` We need to find out what steps are being taken by the military to deal with this very serious problem of phobias,'' the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> Democrat told a news conference. On Monday he wrote to <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> seeking detailed information about how the Pentagon screens recruits for potential mental health problems. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>'s office said the secretary would not have any comment because the letter had n't yet been received. <PERSON> Bilirakis </PERSON>' letter referred to the March 2 death of Airman Recruit <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON>, 19, of <LOCATION> Appleton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, who drowned during an elite rescue swimmer training program at the <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, Naval Air Station. A <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> investigator is now deliberating whether five swimming instructors and a commanding officer should be court-martialed because force was used to stop <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON> from leaving the pool where he drowned. Testimony at a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> preliminary hearing indicated <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON> had a phobia about being pulled under water. <PERSON> Bilirakis </PERSON> held his news conference along with members of the <ORGANIZATION> Phobic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, who said <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON>'s case highlights the dangers of phobias. Phobias are defined as persistent, irrational fears of a specific object, activity or situation which results in a compelling desire by an individual to avoid the fearful stimulus. <PERSON> Bilirikis </PERSON>, citing statistics from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, said `` phobias are the number one mental disorder in this nation and one out of every eight people suffer from some sort of phobia.'' According to <PERSON> Bilirakis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON>'s death may have been avoided had his phobia been recognized before he entered the training program. <PERSON> Bilirakis </PERSON> said nothing on the military medical forms filled out by recruits addresses phobias. `` Additionally, I am told there is nothing in the military medical procedures requiring a doctor to ask about specific mental health disorders at all.''
