<SECOND>AM-USDA-Coca,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>USDA Greenhouse is Site of Battle in Federal War on Cocaine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> researchers are growing coca plants in a $ 1 million-a-year search for ways to eradicate South American crops destined for processing into cocaine, officials said Monday. Between 400 and 600 plants are being grown at two <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> research sites, one a greenhouse near <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and the other an outdoor location in an undisclosed, warm-weather area, said Dr. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Knipling </PERSON>, associate deputy administrator for the <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s national program staff. <PERSON> Knipling </PERSON> said all of the plants used in the experiment are incinerated afterward and that no cocaine is produced from them. Researchers earlier had grown opium poppies in <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and marijuana in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as part of <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s research into ways to stem production of narcotics. The priority changed two years ago because of growing use by Americans of cocaine and crack, a cocaine derivative, <PERSON> Knipling </PERSON> said. The project was spotlighted in a report published in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> on Sunday. <PERSON> Knipling </PERSON> estimated the cost of the program at about $ 1 million a year. He said part of the funds come from the research service's regular budget and the rest by the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> `` There is absolutely none being developed into cocaine,'' <PERSON> Knipling </PERSON> said. `` ... It's not possible, not at our agricultural facilities.'' He confirmed that the seeds were brought to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and said a number of herbicides have been tested for use against the plant. The chief herbicide recommended to the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> for use against coca is tebutherion, a product manufactured by <ORGANIZATION> Eli </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lilly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> under the trade name <PERSON> Spike </PERSON>. <PERSON> Knipling </PERSON> said it is used in considerable quantities in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to clear brush in areas where food crops do not grow. Guards, alarms and wire fences are being used to keep out intruders at the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> installations, <PERSON> Knipling </PERSON> said. He refused to disclose the precise whereabouts of either of the growing sites. The issue first surfaced when the former head of the project, <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Gentner </PERSON>, said in interviews that he had resigned in April to protest what he described as the failure of the Agriculture and State departments to examine adequately the potential dangers from use of the herbicide. <PERSON> Knipling </PERSON> said there had been considerable pressure from various places in the administration to get on with approval of <PERSON> Spike </PERSON> for use against coca. `` We've been under an extensive sense of urgency coming from the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and, of course, the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, itself, that this is a high-priority project,'' he said. <PERSON> Knipling </PERSON> said there had been `` frequent calls and visits'' to the research service that intensified the pressure. He also said it was intensified by demands from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the public for action to combat drugs. <PERSON> Knipling </PERSON> contended that illicit cocaine production in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is doing far more to endanger the environment than would use of tebutherion. He said there was little doubt that the coca leaves were being heavily sprayed with pesticides, which could cause harm. Moreover, he said, sulfuric acid and other chemicals being used to process the coca into cocaine are undoubtedly dumped into streams when the manufacturing process is over.
</TEXT>
