<HEAD>Funeral For Stuntman Who Took Fall For John Wayne, Others</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Friends and relatives gathered Monday to bury veteran movie stunt man <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberson </PERSON>, who for decades took falls for <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> and even broke limbs on behalf of the Duke. <PERSON> Roberson </PERSON>, 69, died of cancer last Wednesday at Mercy Hospital in <LOCATION> Bakersfield </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Roberson </PERSON> first doubled for <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> in the 1949 film `` The Fighting Kentuckian,'' and he retired in 1976 after working with <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> on the actor's final film, `` The Shootist.'' `` He could do any stunt I could do. But the money people could n't afford to let him get hurt, so I was the one who ended up in stitches,'' <PERSON> Roberson </PERSON> said in a 1984 interview. During nearly three decades of stunts for <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON>, <PERSON> Roberson </PERSON> cracked his back, twisted an ankle and broke ribs and arms. He also did stunt work for <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Peck </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON>, <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> <PERSON> Gable </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who sent him a telegram after he became ill last October. After retirement, <PERSON> Roberson </PERSON> raised thoroughbred horses on his ranch south of <LOCATION> Bakersfield </LOCATION>. He also was the subject of a book titled `` The Fall Guy,'' by <PERSON> Bodie </PERSON> <PERSON> Thoene </PERSON>, which later was the basis of the television series by the same name starring <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Majors </PERSON>. `` He was known as the finest stunt man in <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> and also the best director of action scenes,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Thoene </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Glennville </LOCATION>. `` He's one of the last of them. There are n't too many left like him.'' <PERSON> Roberson </PERSON> is survived by his wife, <PERSON> Dolly </PERSON> <PERSON> Mae </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberson </PERSON>, four daughters, a sister and several grandchildren.
