<HEAD>Premiers Have ``Very Friendly'' Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EMEL ANIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VOULIAGMENI, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The prime ministers of rivals <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> held discussions `` in a very friendly atmosphere'' Monday of problems that only last year brought the two <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies close to war. As they talked outside the capital, about 2,000 <ORGANIZATION> Greek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cypriot </ORGANIZATION>, Armenian and Kurdish demonstrators in the city burned <LOCATION> Turkish </LOCATION> flags outside the <ORGANIZATION> Turkish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> and shouted `` Fire for the Turkish dogs!'' Hundreds of helmeted riot police guarded the embassy building but there were no clashes, witnesses said. No signs emerged of a breakthrough on the major disputes over <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Aegean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> during Monday's one hour of talks between Premiers <PERSON> Andreas </PERSON> <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Turgut </PERSON> <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mesut </PERSON> <PERSON> Yilmaz </PERSON>, the But Turkish foreign minister, told reporters later: `` The meeting was held in a very friendly atmosphere and all bilateral problems and international issues were handled,'' <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON> began a three-day visit to <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> on Monday, the first by a Turkish premier in 36 years. Pro-government and opposition Greek newspapers both gave him a cool reception. `` Frozen Smiles'' was the headline in 24 Hours, an independent <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> daily. `` The country receives <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON> with a cold heart,'' said the pro-government <ORGANIZATION> Avriani </ORGANIZATION>. In separate statements before the talks started, both leaders made clear they did not expect immediate major advances on the main disputes. On Monday night, <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON> was guest of honor at a dinner beside the the swimming pool of a seaside hotel in <LOCATION> Vouliagmeni </LOCATION>, outside <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION>, where he and <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> are staying. `` There is no room for petty designs, one-sided gains and short-sighted tactics,'' <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON> said in his speech, in an apparent reference to Greek demands that Turkish troops leave <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> said in his speech he had revived an earlier proposal for demilitarization of the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> island and establishing a joint <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cypriot </LOCATION> and Turkish Cypriot police force. `` It's clear that progress in Greek-Turkish relations is directly affected by the solution of the <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> problem ... and this is directly linked with the withdrawal of troops from the island,'' he said. <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON> will drive into downtown <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> on Tuesday to lay a wreath at the Monument of the Unknown Soldier outside <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, then hold more private talks with <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> in the evening. <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON> began his visit with an appeal for patience on the `` the long road -LRB- to peace -RRB- on which we have started journeying.'' `` We must have realistic expectations, otherwise the disappointments to be suffered will take us away from our main goal,'' he told reporters. `` The problems go back a long time and as solutions were delayed some of these problems petrified and prejudices increased.'' When <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON> arrived at the airport, only a few red-and-white Turkish flags were displayed and a Greek commando squad in camouflage battle-dress formed the honor guard. The neighbors came to the brink of war in March 1987 over oil-drilling rights in the <LOCATION> Aegean </LOCATION> seabed. The near-clash apparently convinced <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> to alter his no-dialogue policy toward <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> and seek friendlier relations. <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> wants <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> to pull its troops out of northern <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> and agree on a joint appeal to the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to settle the <LOCATION> Aegean </LOCATION> continental shelf dispute. <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON> says <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> will not be pressured into withdrawing its forces from <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> and prefers Greek-Turkish talks to solve the Aegean problem. The soldiers were sent after a brief Greek-led coup in July 1974.
