<HEAD>Shultz Urges Signing of Non-Proliferation Treaty</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with Shultz delivering speech,
deletes reference to `prepared remarks' and adds more quotes,
details; PICKS up 13th graf pvs bgng, The U.N. session ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said `` proliferation is winning the race against disarmament,'' and told the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> on Monday that all nations should sign the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> secretary of state said the danger of proliferation is `` most acute'' in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, meaning <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and its rival <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. Both have refused to sign the treaty and accuse each other of developing nuclear weapons. He said that 136 nations have signed the 20-year-old treaty and `` there is no good reason why every nation should not make such a commitment. It is a contribution each and every state can make to a safer world.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> also said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is `` concerned about the introduction of advanced missiles into the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war'' because they have killed civilians. Hundreds of people were killed on both sides earlier this year when <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> rained missiles on each other's cities. Most of the weapons were believed to be Scud missiles of an old Soviet design, some of them equipped with boosters for longer range. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> address to a special <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> session on disarmament came a week after Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> called on the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to join a permament nuclear test ban. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> did not respond to a series of Soviet proposals that won praise from many in the 159-member assembly. In his speech, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> outlined American achievements in arms control and said <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s `` top priority'' in the field is concluding a U.S.-Soviet treaty to cut strategic nuclear arsenals by 50 percent. `` Does anyone doubt that the spread of nuclear weapons threatens regional and global security?'' he said. `` What state believes that, if it now acquired nuclear weapons, its rivals would not do the same?'' Now that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> have agreed to reduce their nuclear arsenals, `` it would be tragic for other countries to pursue the capability to cross the nuclear threshhold,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. He said <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> is the area of greatest danger, and urged countries in the region `` to take concrete steps to meet this urgent challenge. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> is prepared to work with countries inside and outside the region to find a lasting solution to the danger of proliferation that satisfies all parties.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> was among the final few of more than 100 speakers who have addressed the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> since the special session began two weeks ago. In his remarks about the Iran-Iraq war, which began in September 1980, he said: `` We already are seeing signs of a dangerous new arms race which will put at risk countries far removed from the gulf region itself.'' Use of the missiles and the killing of civilians makes a peace settlement more difficult, he said. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> session has been divided over key disarmament questions and diplomatic observers said it will be difficult to draft a final document which can satisfy most nations and be adopted by consensus. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and Western allies have called for limited, pragmatic steps in arms control, continued respect for nuclear deterrence, a limited role for the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> and recognition that bilateral arms talks must supersede multilateral efforts. They say the treaty on intermediate-range nuclear weapons and some progress in U.S.-Soviet talks on 50-percent cuts on strategic weapons show that bilateral efforts should be allowed to continue unencumbered by a multilateral apparatus. Western diplomats also have said that conventional disarmament is as important as nuclear disarmament and urged poor developing nations which clamor for nuclear disarmament to cut their own mounting expenditure in conventional armies. After the speeches end Tuesday or Wednesday, groups will begin drafting resolutions and a final document for this third special session on disarmament in 10 years. But if the divisions are too great and the disarmament proposals too sweeping and utopian, Western nations are expected to demand a vote, making consensus unlikely.
