<HEAD>Jaruzelski Appeals For Reconciliation, But Not With Solidarity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Polish leader Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> appealed Monday for national reconciliation and expressed willingness to legalize new associations and cooperate with `` communities'' outside official life _ but not with Solidarity. `` We can talk to anyone, as long as he is not a client, especially a paid one, of a foreign court,'' <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> said. He referred to grants of $ 1 million the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government gave to Solidarity after it became the first free trade union federation in the Soviet bloc. <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> gave the major policy address at the start of a two-day meeting of the 230-member <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>' -LRB- Communist -RRB- Party. He is party first secretary and president of the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Janusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Onyszkiewicz </PERSON>, national spokesman for the now outlawed <ORGANIZATION> Solidarity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> federation </ORGANIZATION>, said in a telephone interview that any claim that Solidarity is disloyal to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> did not merit a response. He noted that both <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> and the communist government have accepted <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid in the past and added, `` We are in very strange company.'' It was the first Central Committee plenum since a series of strikes between April 25 and May 10. Five factories were struck and 25 other plants endured brief stoppages or strike threats in the strongest labor action since Solidarity was suspended in December 1981 and subsequently outlawed. Solidarity had been chartered by the government during nationwide strikes in August 1980. <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> accused the leaders of the recent strikes of an `` almost pathological lack of responsibility'' and said they could not be `` an objectively credible partner in dialogue.'' But he said authorities are ready to talk with critics who want to improve the state. `` National reconciliation is a basic condition and one of the goals of socialist renewal,'' <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> said. `` It is broader today than in past years.'' <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> said a planned new law on associations would lift administrative restrictions and grant the associations more freedom. In the meantime, officials should legally register new, `` socially justified'' groups, he said. He mentioned no groups specifically. Indications have emerged that at least three suppressed groups _ the pro-private enterprise <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>; the Polish chapter of the <ORGANIZATION> PEN </ORGANIZATION> writer's club and the <LOCATION> Dziekania </LOCATION> political discussion club _ may soon be registered. About 300 mostly non-controversial private associations were legalized last year, but applications of many other groups were not approved, including local chapters of Solidarity and the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Students </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> said `` ideas and practices are crystalizing slowly'' for cooperation with what he called independent communities that have refused to join PRON, the official national unity organization. He proposed a permanent wage-price commission with representatives of labor, management and consumers that would seek a social consensus for price increases. He said this would avoid periodic across-the-board price increases like one this year and instead aim at a floating system with prices evolving gradually. <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> noted that Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> will visit <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> next month and said the trip will add a `` new, significant chapter'' to Polish-Soviet relations.
