<HEAD>Soviets Turn Up Volume on Afghan Complaints</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-UN-Afghanistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and Afghan President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> on Monday warned of `` resolute retaliatory measures'' if <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> continues to help Moslem rebels fighting the Afghan government. The warning, the first of its kind directly from <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, came as sources in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> reported that <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> forces returned to some cities in eastern <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> to fight guerrillas who raided posts defended by Afghan troops. Since shortly before the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit that ended last week, the Soviets have been warning <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that continuing to arm the guerrillas violated the accords signed in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> on May 15. Under those accords, the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> agreed to withdraw its 100,300 troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> by Feb. 15. Western intelligence agencies put the number of Soviet forces involved as up to 115,000. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> did not issue any warnings about <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> during the summit, said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials, who predicted then that the Soviets would complete the withdrawal. Thousands of Soviet troops already have returned home. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials rejected Soviet complaints about aid still flowing to the Moslem rebels, noting an exchange of letters between <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> that each side would arm its Afghan allies as long as the other did so. A joint Najib-Gorbachev statement distributed over the official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency said: `` The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> believed that the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Mission monitoring compliance with the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords would adopt ... effective measures to curb the practice -LRB- of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s aiding the guerrillas -RRB- which, if continued would make it necessary to undertake the most resolute retaliatory steps.'' <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> had made a similar warning after meeting with <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>. And <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> lashed out against <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> for maintaining what he called an `` infrastructure of interference _ military camps, training centers for the armed groups of the opposition, all manner of subversive, terroristic groups'' on Pakistani territory. He also attacked a White House statement that he said tried to justify <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s continued supply of arms to the rebels, saying the <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION> rejected a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> proposal for mutual termination of aid. `` The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> never agreed to its military aid to the legitimate government in the Republic of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> being linked in any form with arms supplies to the insurgent illegal groups which bank on the forcible overthrow of the government,'' the statement said.
