<HEAD>Threatens Execution of Those Dumping Toxic Wastes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The military government said Monday it will execute anyone convicted of involvement in dumping foreign toxic waste in <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Duro </PERSON> <PERSON> Onabule </PERSON>, spokesman for President <PERSON> Ibrahim </PERSON> <PERSON> Babangida </PERSON>, said the death penalty also might apply to foreigners connected with the dumping of more than 2,000 tons of chemical waste near the town of <LOCATION> Koko </LOCATION>, including poisonous and radioactive material. <PERSON> Koko </PERSON> is 150 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION>, capital of this West African nation. Prince <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Momoh </PERSON>, the information minister, said at a separate news conference that 15 people had been arrested in the Koko dumping. He did not identify them but said an Italian who directed the operation, <PERSON> Gianfranco </PERSON> <PERSON> Raffaelli </PERSON>, fled the country after newspapers reported the dumping. `` There will be no mercy on this issue,'' Onabule told reporters. `` We would rather do away with 20 Nigerians, stupid Nigerians, than allow them to endanger the lives of millions of Nigerians and fellow Africans.'' He said the government seized the land on which the waste was dumped. Last Friday the government said it had seized an Italian ship that would be forced to remove the waste and recalled its ambassador from <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. An Italian firm was accused of dumping the waste for European companies. Police guarding the site in <LOCATION> Bendel </LOCATION> state were withdrawn Sunday for their own safety, the Nes Agency of <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> reported. It said confirmation by chemists that the waste included poisonous substances prompted removal of the policemen, who had been stationed around the site to keep the public away. Scientists urged anyone who had been near the site to have a medical examination. Attempts by European and American companies to dump toxic waste in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> have provoked protests in recent weeks. Five Congolese, including three senior government officials, were arrested after a dumping scheme was discovered there. <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION> arrested a Norwegian businessman and charged him with complicity in dumping American waste on an island near the capital, <LOCATION> Conakry </LOCATION>. Several other countries said they had refused lucrative offers from Western companies seeking permission to dump chemical waste.
