<HEAD>PRECEDE Washington</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S. Urges Extradition of Alleged Palestinian Terrorist</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with new info Greek response and changes
to conform</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A district attorney has asked for more information in his examination of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> request for extradition of a Palestinian accused in the bombings of two American jetliners, judicial sources said Monday. They said the request for <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Rashid </PERSON>'s extradition `` was n't backed by hard enough evidence that would support opening extradition proceedings. District Attorney <PERSON> Elias </PERSON> <PERSON> Spyropoulos </PERSON>, who is handling the case, told <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities Greek law sets a two-month time limit for providing needed information in extradition requests, according to the sources, who spoke on condition they not be identified. `` What the Americans have so far provided wo n't do, and if the additional evidence has n't landed on the district attorney's two months from now, the proceedings ca n't be pursued,'' one source said. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Monday that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> asked <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> for the immediate extradition of <PERSON> Rashid </PERSON>, `` a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> terrorist wanted in connection'' with the August 1982 explosion aboard a <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> passenger jet in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. The blast killed one person and wounded 15. <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was heartened by the Greek government's June 7 statement saying it was dedicated to the international fight against terrorism. `` We strongly believe that the most effective way to fight terrorism in this case is to expeditiously begin extradition proceedings against <PERSON> Rashid </PERSON>,'' he added. It was the first time the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration publicly acknowledged it was seeking <PERSON> Rashid </PERSON>, 34. American officials admitted privately last week that they were seeking <PERSON> Rashid </PERSON>'s extradition but declined to make the case public, citing the delicacy of the negotiations. <PERSON> Rashid </PERSON> was arrested at the <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> June 1 by Greek police acting on information from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, according to police. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said last week <PERSON> Rashid </PERSON> also is wanted in connection with a 1986 explosion aboard a <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> plane flying over <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> in which four people were killed. <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> did not mention that case in his brief statement on <PERSON> Rashid </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision to publicly comment on the case came after a <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> security official in <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> said earlier Monday that <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> would try <PERSON> Rashid </PERSON> on the charge of using a false Syrian passport to enter the country. If convicted on that count, <PERSON> Rashid </PERSON> could be given a jail term of 1 -LCB- to two years to be served before an extradition hearing took place, said the security official, speaking on condition of anonymity. Government spokesman <PERSON> Yiannis </PERSON> <PERSON> Roubatis </PERSON> declined to comment on the case. <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> has followed a similar procedure in delaying extradition proceedings until a suspect served a misdemeanor sentence. A Jordanian arrested at the Greek-Turkish border in 1982 is still awaiting extradition to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, where he is wanted for allegedly plotting an attack at a <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> synagogue that killed a boy. The Jordanian, <PERSON> Abdel </PERSON> <PERSON> Osama </PERSON> <PERSON> Al-Zomor </PERSON>, served a 20-month sentence for smuggling explosives before the extradition request was heard. Although the request eventually was approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Al-Zomor </PERSON> was sentenced again for being found in possession of an illegal weapon in his prison cell and remains in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. Premier <PERSON> Andreas </PERSON> <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON>'s Socialist government, which has good relations with the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, has been accused of being lax in fighting terrorism.
