<HEAD>Eight Die In Plane Crash, Second Air Tragedy In Two Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA PLATA, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Eight people died when a private plane with engine trouble crashed while trying to make an emergency landing Monday night. It was the country's second fatal air accident in as many days. Air authorities in <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plata </LOCATION>, 30 miles south of the capital <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION>, said the pilot of the Havilland Dove twin-engine craft told the control tower he was having problems with one engine. He requested emergency landing rights, which were immediately granted, officials said. But the plane crashed in <LOCATION> Arana </LOCATION>, a community five miles from the airport, police at the scene said. Eight bodies were recovered, including that of a police inspector and two children, ages eight and nine, police said. The ninth victim was taken to a local hospital in serious condition, police said. On Sunday, an <ORGANIZATION> Austral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> DC-9 jetliner smashed into a hillside in heavy fog and burst into flames outside Posadas in northeastern <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. All 22 aboard were killed. The cause of that fiery accident, which claimed the lives of 15 passengers and seven crew members, is under investigation. Two of the victims were Japanese and a third was French. Austral is a private carrier bought last year from the state and competes with the government carrier <ORGANIZATION> Aerolineas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Argentinas </ORGANIZATION> on domestic routes.
