<HEAD>Report: 350 Trade Unionists Killed in 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At least 350 trade unionists were killed and 7,500 arrested worldwide during 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Confederation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unions </ORGANIZATION> said in a report released Tuesday. Despite improvements in some countries, `` the overall picture remains grim,'' the <ORGANIZATION> ICFTU </ORGANIZATION> said in its annual survey of anti-union violence. `` There is a tendency among governments to consider respect for trade union rights as less important than certain other human rights,'' it said. The rights violations occurred in both dictatorships and democracies, according to the Brussels-based <ORGANIZATION> ICFTU </ORGANIZATION>, which has 141 affiliates in 97 non-communist nations and claims it represents 87 million workers. Its 58-page report said violations last year of union rights ranged from denying the right of association to `` murder, torture and imprisonment.'' The <ORGANIZATION> ICFTU </ORGANIZATION> report said Latin American unionists faced the most ruthless treatment. It said that in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, more than `` 200 killings occurred related to disputes over landownership, many of which concerned leaders and members of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Confederation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>.'' `` There is evidence'' most of the victims were slain by killers hired by landowners, according to the report. In <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, paramilitary groups killed at least 74 trade unionists and `` the real figure is probably much higher,'' it said. The report stated: `` The most flagrant trade union rights violations are undoubtedly taking place in countries under dictatorship, irrespective of their ideological orientation. `` However, in many countries, even those with long established democratic traditions, there are also restrictions and infringements of these rights.'' The <ORGANIZATION> ICFTU </ORGANIZATION> said laws in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> undermined the rights of trade unions and `` in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> serious cases of union-busting continue to occur.'' It gave this summary: _ <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>: In most nations, unions are controlled by the parties in power that forbid rivals, ban or curb the right to strike and interfere with the organization of union activities In <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>, the trade union movement must by law follow Marxist theory and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> `` totally negates fundamental human rights.'' _ <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>: `` Infringements of trade union rights continue to occur on a wide scale <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>, among others, continue to violently suppress union activities.'' In <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, the human rights situation generally has improved but `` specific violations of trade union rights continue to occur'' including detention without trial and persecution of union members. _ <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>: In communist nations `` freedom of association, free collective bargaining and the right to strike do not exist. Anti-communist <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> used `` extreme police violence'' against strikers. _ <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>: The introduction of economic reforms in some East European nations did not boost trade union rights In <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, the courts rejected more than 30 applications for recognition by `` local enterprise sections'' belonging to the outlawed Solidarity union federation. Romanian police broke up a demonstration of union workers in November. In <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, `` the most outrageous attack on basic trade union rights in recent years continues to be the ban'' on union membership in the government's intelligence gathering center at <LOCATION> Cheltenham </LOCATION>. _ <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>: Some Arab nations allow only a single trade union and in others, such as <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oman </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Qatar </LOCATION>, trade unions are banned Emergency regulations remain in force in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> `` to restrict human and trade union rights,'' the report said.
