<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs, June 14, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Ray Sharkey Back as Mobster in Return of `Wiseguy'</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 You viewers who never understood why friends and co-workers were mad for a TV villain can catch up beginning Wednesday when CBS reruns the `` Wiseguy'' episodes guest-starring <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharkey </PERSON> as mobster <PERSON> Sonny </PERSON> <PERSON> Steelgrave </PERSON>. `` Wiseguy'' stars <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Wahl </PERSON> as undercover agent <PERSON> Vinnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Terranova </PERSON>, who was himself so charmed by <PERSON> Steelgrave </PERSON> he almost went over to the other side. He has since gone on to chase new villains. `` This is a whole new way to do television,'' said <PERSON> Sharkey </PERSON>. `` You can get actors who do mostly movies, because you've got a story with a beginning, middle and end. It runs longer than a miniseries and you can develop a character. I've heard someone refer to this as a soap opera for tough guys. `` But I wo n't be back on ` Wiseguy' next season. I'm history. The only way I could come back is in a flashback. We may do that. We've gotten so many letters asking for me that I think we should give them something There's even a <ORGANIZATION> Sonny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steelgrave </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. They write us each week asking us to bring back <PERSON> Sonny </PERSON>.'' Though the Steelgrave episodes that opened `` Wiseguy'' last fall attracted a following, the show was up against <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Cheers'' and `` Night Court'' on Thursday night and did n't get big ratings. CBS is hoping that will change if a new audience catches the show this summer. Wednesday's episode is the two-hour movie that introduced the character. <PERSON> Sharkey </PERSON>'s portrayal of <PERSON> Steelgrave </PERSON>, with his murderous, mercurial charm, has been likened to <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Cagney </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Cody </PERSON> <PERSON> Jarrett </PERSON> in `` White Heat,'' or <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Bogart </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> <PERSON> Mantee </PERSON> in `` The Petrified Forest'' and <PERSON> Mad </PERSON> <PERSON> Dog </PERSON> <PERSON> Earle </PERSON> in `` High Sierra.'' <PERSON> Sonny </PERSON>'s apocalypse is nearly as spectacular as <PERSON> Cagney </PERSON>'s in the gasoline refinery in `` White Heat.'' `` I meet people who memorize <PERSON> Sonny </PERSON>'s dialogue and say it back to me,'' said <PERSON> Sharkey </PERSON>. `` Just like ` The Rocky Horror Show.''' The role in `` Wiseguy'' was a much-needed boost for <PERSON> Sharkey </PERSON>. He had made a big splash playing an ambitious manager in `` The Idolmaker'' in 1980, but his career dissolved into alcohol and drugs. `` I went at it full-blown,'' he said. `` It was fun for a while. Then it got crazy and by 1985 it was sickening. I lost great parts to guys who became big stars. I could n't get insured. I'd turn in my urine tests knowing I would never pass. `` I spent several years in and out of hospitals. I'd dry out, do a movie and end up back in the hospital. I finally found a place that dealt with the problem and not the personalities. I spent 62 days there, came out and went right to work.'' He was only four days out of the rehabilitation program when he began the role on `` Wiseguy.'' He is currently starring as a Puerto Rican angel in `` Wired,'' based on the controversial <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodward </PERSON> book about <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Belushi </PERSON>, who died of a drug overdose. The angel is a fantasy element added to the movie. <PERSON> Sharkey </PERSON> says it's like playing the dark side of `` It's a Wonderful Life.'' The angel picks up <PERSON> Belushi </PERSON> at the morgue `` and shows him the error of his ways.'' `` It's great,'' <PERSON> Sharkey </PERSON> said, `` because he gets in all the <ORGANIZATION> Blues </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> dance numbers and the ` Saturday Night Live' comedy sketches.'' In August, <PERSON> Sharkey </PERSON> is set to co-star with <PERSON> Jacqueline </PERSON> <PERSON> Bisset </PERSON> in the romantic comedy `` Scenes From a Class Struggle in <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>.'' In September, he is slated to play attorney <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohn </PERSON>, the former aide to Sen. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> who died of AIDS. After finishing the `` Wiseguy'' shooting in <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Sharkey </PERSON> went to <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> for the movie `` Act of Piracy,'' playing `` a really bad guy, a gun smuggler and modern-day pirate in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>. Those guys'll kill your whole family and take your boat to run guns or drugs.'' `` Sonny's different. He was a man who could carry out his own brand of ethics. He did it with such charm and lack of guilt. And, I think the audience likes to see bad boys having fun. <PERSON> Sonny </PERSON> was a man who was very family-oriented. His attitude was ` Do n't judge me by what I do for a living.'''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Elsewhere in television: PODIATRIST TO THE STARS _ Dr. M.H. <PERSON> Sward </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> podiatrist whose patients have included <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Gleason </PERSON>, <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Pidgeon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Groucho </PERSON> <PERSON> Marx </PERSON>, has turned actor at the age of 59. <PERSON> Sward </PERSON>, known professionally as <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ward </ORGANIZATION>, has just done a commercial for Cheerios breakfast cereal. He also did a non-speaking role in <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Bronson </PERSON>'s `` Messenger of Death.'' He got the acting bug when he attended a commercials workshop and was signed by an agent.
</TEXT>
