<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 26</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Shuttle Countdown</HEAD>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Visitors entering <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> McCartney </PERSON>'s office ca n't miss this sign: `` If it is n't safe, say so.'' As director of the Kennedy Space Center, <PERSON> McCartney </PERSON> is overseeing the preparation of Discovery for the first post-Challenger space shuttle flight later this summer. The sign sums up his approach. If anyone, anywhere in the system, has a concern, that person should report it. `` I'd rather call a timeout to take a look at those concerns than to move on without checking thoroughly,'' <PERSON> McCartney </PERSON> said in an interview. `` I do n't want anyone on launch day to say, ` Is there something I overlooked, something I should have reported and did n't?' We want to be sure we have done everything humanly possible to make this vehicle as safe as it can be before it flies.'' Several workers have come forward with legitimate concerns. Other reports have proved unfounded, and have caused processing delays. <PERSON> McCartney </PERSON> says he'd rather be safe than sorry. <PERSON> McCartney </PERSON>, 57, was a lieutenant general in charge of the Air Force Space Division when <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> administrator <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> tapped him to be center director. He was part of the space agency overhaul after the Jan. 28, 1986, explosion of space shuttle Challenger. He retired last year from the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and continued in the job as a civilian. <PERSON> McCartney </PERSON> has gained a reputation as a `` hands-on'' director who takes a personal interest in his 13,000 workers and the shuttle hardware that is checked out, assembled and readied for launch here. He pays close attention to the processing through daily staff meetings, weekly sessions with center managers and monthly conferences with key <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> shuttle officials. said. `` I also get out and talk with the people,'' <PERSON> McCartney </PERSON> says. `` I want to know what they are thinking. Almost every day I personally check the hardware _ the orbiter, the solid rocket motors. If I get a free hour, I say it's time to go out and kick some tires, so I get in the car and go out there. `` The workers talk freely with me. They discuss a full spectrum of concerns, from processing concerns to work hours. They do n't feel intimidated It's a good repartee, and I feel good about it.'' When he first took over as director, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s target for resuming shuttle flights was February 1988. That date has slipped several months, and, while the delays have been frustrating, he says they have been necessary. <PERSON> McCartney </PERSON> said the emphasis on quality and safety has created enormous paperwork, or flight documentation, as he calls it. `` We close out flight documentation in an orderly way,'' he said. `` We are not going to move hardware to the next station until it is ready. It's time-consuming, but, when in doubt, do n't. No one is in a hurry to make a mistake.''
</TEXT>
