<FIRST>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek Adv26   06-13 0962</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Theater Week, Adv 26,0985</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv26</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 26</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Godspell,'' the joyous little pop musical that put the Bible on Broadway, is back in town. The show, now playing at the Lamb's Theater, was directed by <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Scardino </PERSON> who has a long association with the hit musical. He played <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> for more than 1,000 performances during the show's seven-year run in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` Godspell,'' based on the Gospel of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Matthew </LOCATION>, is one of those classic show business tales of success: Young man -LRB- <PERSON> John-Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Tebelak </PERSON> -RRB- writes show as a master's project at <ORGANIZATION> Carnegie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. Show gets done on a shoestring in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> at a small experimental theater off-off-Broadway. Gets favorable reviews. A revised version, with new songs by <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON>, opens at a larger off-Broadway theater and eventually makes its way to <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION>. At one time during the 1970s, there were 30 companies of the musical playing around the world. <PERSON> Scardino </PERSON> first came to `` Godspell'' in 1972 at the age of 24. He starred as <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> in the <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> company of the show and later came to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> for a two-year run. `` Finally, with shinsplints, a sprained ankle and nodes on my vocal chords, I gave up the ghost and left the show,'' <PERSON> Scardino </PERSON> says. `` After it had been running five years off-Broadway, I was asked to open up the Broadway company. `` I was flattered. So I wrapped ankles, visited the throat doctor and went on,'' says the director who started in show business at the age of 12 as an actor. Throughout its long run in the 1970s, `` Godspell,'' a gentle, free-spirited retelling of the last seven days of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON>, kept slowly changing. `` The show became a little bloated, and the simplicity disappeared,'' <PERSON> Scardino </PERSON> says. `` Unlike a regular show where someone directs it and the production stays that way, <PERSON> John-Michael </PERSON> -LRB- who died in 1985 -RRB- was basically the overseer of this troupe of lunatic actors who had come out of an improvisatory style. He encouraged the show to be flexible and free.'' <PERSON> Scardino </PERSON> agreed to direct the revival only after discussions with composer <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON>. `` I wanted to stay true to the original intention of the show and still have the freedom to bring it up to date,'' he says. `` I wanted people to think they were watching the original, the show they remembered, even though it is n't.'' Besides changing the musical's prologue, <PERSON> Scardino </PERSON> updated a lot of other material in the show, particularly the jokes and political references. Now there are jokes about <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tammy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> and the crisis in evangelism. <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has also popped up, as has the ubiquitous yuppie. A section of the show that was spoken now has turned into a rap number. `` We've brought it up to the'80s,'' he says. `` Physically, it looks the same as it did when it first opened, but the idiom has been updated.'' For the revival, <PERSON> Scardino </PERSON> hired young actors who had never done `` Godspell'' before. Most had never seen it. He has also used some of their suggestions _ `` they are authentically young'' _ such as incorporating a Pee Wee <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> step into the choreography. He has taken some of their references and things that have come out of their current frame of mind to create the show. `` The things I've learned by playing <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON>, I've tried to pass along to <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Steefel </PERSON> who plays him in this show but without being dictatorial about it,'' <PERSON> Scardino </PERSON> says. `` Everybody else in the musical, I'll just give notes or suggestions. With him, I unconsciously start to act it out or show him and that's wrong. He is the actor.'' The original performers in `` Godspell'' all came out of <ORGANIZATION> Carnegie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION>, now <ORGANIZATION> Carnegie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mellon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. They had been together for four years and had a strong background in an acting technique that involved story theater, the telling of stories and the playing of games. It's a technique not taught much lately, so <PERSON> Scardino </PERSON> asked for _ and got _ an extra week of rehearsal to do theater games such as <PERSON> Blindman </PERSON>, trust exercises and circle games with the new actors. They are exercises dedicated to creating an ensemble unit of actors and break down the social barriers. `` It's the only show in which you have to be deprogrammed when you leave it,'' <PERSON> Scardino </PERSON> laughs. The director feels the musical will find a new audience today, even though it has only been a decade since the show was last seen in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, plus get many of the people who saw it before. `` I'm a'60s person,'' the 40-year-old <PERSON> Scardino </PERSON> says. `` We all thought we were searching for new definitions. We thought we were revolutionaries, either political or spiritual or whatever. But there was a spiritual search alive and a rejection of material values _ or at least we thought so. Then we entered the'80s and we've come into yuppie materialism.'' It was `` Godspell's'' naivete and honesty that attracted people in the 1970s, <PERSON> Scardino </PERSON> says, adding that the musical had a fresh perspective on something that had lost meaning for people _ the Gospel. `` I think we are in a crisis of values now,'' <PERSON> Scardino </PERSON> says. `` Everybody seems to be involved now in another search for meaning or a new search for spiritual values. It's the pendulum swinging, although it has n't swung yet. The kind of joy that ` Godspell' has, the kind of hope that ` Godspell' gives, that is needed. And I think people will come and find it as refreshing as they did before.''
</TEXT>
