<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>GUATEMALA CITY: the soldiers.''</HEAD>
<HEAD>TOMAS:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Sixteen-year-old <PERSON> Tomas </PERSON> has told the director of the orphanage where he has lived for five years that soldiers broke his father's fingers and tortured him in other ways `` to make him confess that he was a guerrilla. `` They shot him three times in the chest,'' the director said. `` He never saw his mother again. Some told him the town was burned.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ANGEL:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Childhope </LOCATION>, an international organization helping street children, has known <PERSON> Angel </PERSON> since not long after he reached the <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> streets in 1984, stealing and already on paint thinner at age 9. One day he began telling <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON> about nightmares he has of seeing his mother killed at their home in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. `` He vividly recalled to me the killing of his father, mother and two brothers,'' he said. The next day, soldiers found the boy asleep at home and brought his little sister and him to a base where his brother was a soldier. `` Soldiers came back to the base one day and said his brother had been killed. Then soldiers, friends of his or his brother's, took them to the border and told them to go across,'' he said. Shortly after arriving in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, he lost track of his sister. One day, the director says, <PERSON> Angel </PERSON> wants to go back to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> to find a younger brother. He has been in and out of a home run by a religious group in the provinces.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 In many children, the trauma is hidden. `` What you can say is that there have been many learning difficulties, many difficulties in relating,'' said <PERSON> Nicole </PERSON> <PERSON> Dagnino </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Enfants </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refugies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monde </ORGANIZATION>, a private French organization that works with refugee children in several countries. Parents who are refugees become depressed, have no jobs, lose their traditional contact with the land. The child, in addition to having to leave his home, loses his father image. `` They have lost all points of reference,'' Ms. <PERSON> Dagnino </PERSON> said. A woman who works with refugee orphans said she had `` several children who go around setting fire to everything.'' But while children in orphanages often fight with each other, she said these do n't. `` It is as if they protect each other,'' she said. Perhaps worse than the direct effects, says <PERSON> Kayayan </PERSON>, is the money that military spending takes away from health, education and other programs to help children and the destruction of those facilities. Adding to the problem is economic crisis in the already-poor region from both the wars and other factors. <ORGANIZATION> UNICEF </ORGANIZATION> says infant and child deaths are on the rise in the region and nearly two out of three of the survivors suffer some degree of malnutrition. A study by the Guatemala-based <ORGANIZATION> Nutrition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> found the nutrition in rural communities of <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> had worsened significantly between 1985 and 1987, a period after the most recent peak in fighting. `` In the war atmosphere of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> it is impossible to collect data,'' the institute's Dr. <PERSON> Hernan </PERSON> <PERSON> Delgado </PERSON> said. `` But it is reasonable to think that with the military and economic situations, there is a worsening in the state of health.'' About 40 percent of children under age 5 in the Central American region are believed to suffer some form of malnutrition. The average includes <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, where conditions traditionally are better. In 1980, 64 percent of the population was below the poverty line and 41 percent could not afford the minimum food basket. But <PERSON> Delgado </PERSON> said worsening nutrition levels or infant and child mortality were `` like the tip of the iceberg,'' the culmination of a series of changes such as more illness or reduced physical activity. `` It may be that it is not as important as all the change that occurs, what that implies in all the children who did n't die,'' he said.
</TEXT>
