<FIRST>s i BC-Africa-ToxicWaste Adv19-1stadd   06-13 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Africa-Toxic Waste, Adv 19-1st add,0775</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>NAIROBI: Third World countries.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Despite the public pronouncements, few expect any quick resolution of the problem. `` Quite a lot of the business is going on somewhere in the twilight,'' said <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Huismans </PERSON>, director of the Geneva-based <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Register </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Potentionally </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Toxic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemicals </ORGANIZATION>, an arm of <ORGANIZATION> UNEP </ORGANIZATION>. `` I think it is economics. I ca n't see any other benefit of receiving this waste.'' Money also is a factor for Western industries, which account for the bulk of the 300 million metric tons of industrial wastes produced annually worldwide. Stringent environmental laws in the West, like those imposed by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, demand on-site disposal facilities that can cost as much as $ 30 million and take years to build. And to ship toxic wastes from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> _ which churns out 10 million metric tons of wastes a year _ across the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to a landfill in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> costs about $ 800 a barrel. Industrialized countries also are under public pressure to keep toxic landfills away from rapidly expanding residential areas. In return for $ 92.6 million, the <LOCATION> Congo </LOCATION>, a nation of 1.8 million people, agreed to accept 1 million metric tons for storage or incineration over eight years. The `` heavily polluted chemical waste,'' as it was described, was to be shippped from the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belguim </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Santen </PERSON>, the Rottendam-based cargo firm hired to transport the wastes, made no effort to conceal the deal. T.H. <PERSON> Looyschelder </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> Van </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Santen </ORGANIZATION>, said the firm saw a double advantage of transporting toxic waste to <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. `` Not only do we have a cheap way of disposing of waste, but the Third World will be provided with money, knowhow and infrastructure,'' he was quoted as saying. The company said similar negotiations were under way with <LOCATION> Niger </LOCATION>, in north-central <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Santen </PERSON> was forced to put the <LOCATION> Congo </LOCATION> deal on hold after a spate of negative publicity. `` Before the transports to <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> would take place, we would have taken samples and analyses of the chemicals involved to check whether the transports would be within the regulations of the various countries involved,'' <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Hulswit </PERSON>, deputy director of <ORGANIZATION> Van </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Santen </ORGANIZATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>. `` But now that the press has painted the picture of us being involved in illegal activities by imposing dangerous materials on Third World countries against their will, we're bowing out.'' <PERSON> Huismans </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> official, said <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> countries are n't prepared to handle the West's toxic wastes `` In principal, there is nothing terribly wrong with dumping toxic wastes in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> providing the receiving countries can properly handle the wastes,'' he said. `` Invariably, most of the countries who accept the wastes are importing a problem that they initially may not know is a problem.'' <PERSON> Huismans </PERSON>, a toxicologist, said that most hazardous wastes shipped to <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> are so vaguely described that it is impossible to know from their names whether they are dangerous or not. Parts of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> long have been toxic wastes dumps. As those landfills became full, <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> became the new dumping ground beginning five years ago. <ORGANIZATION> UNEP </ORGANIZATION> has drafted a Global Convention on the <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transboundary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movements </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hazardous </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wastes </ORGANIZATION>, which was discussed an an international toxic waste conference sponsored by <ORGANIZATION> UNEP </ORGANIZATION> June 6-10 in <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> UNEP </ORGANIZATION>'s executive director, <PERSON> Mostafa </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tolba </PERSON>, said it would be legally binding on signatory nations once approved by the 50-nation group, probably next year. `` Most of the countries are not equipped to handle such imports,'' <PERSON> Tolba </PERSON> said in a statement. `` That's why we must work to get the international treaty into force to ensure adequate control of movements of hazardous wastes crossing frontiers. ... `` We have received information on planned exports of millions of metric tons of hazardous wastes from <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies to Third World countries such as <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bissau </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Congo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Benin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Huismans </PERSON> urged preventative work on possible health hazards. `` I do n't think we should wait until such proof is found,'' he said. `` So far, it has been difficult to prove that any wastes have led to serious effects on human health. But it takes time for these things to develop.'' Said Sey, the Gambian foreign minister: `` I think people have a concept that <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> is the jungle. `` If you can not dump it in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, just dump it in the jungle because it is just trees and animals and those Africans do n't matter.''
</TEXT>
