<FIRST>s i BC-NATOChanges Adv19-1stadd   06-13 0797</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-NATO Changes, Adv 19-1st add,0818</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>BRUSSELS: be made.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 A key turning point was <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s dramatic call in January 1986 for the global elimination of all nuclear weapons by the year 2000, including a first-phase scrapping of INF missiles in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> by 1990. Ten months later, at a meeting in <LOCATION> Reykjavik </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>, he and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> agreed in principle to eliminate all but 100 INF missiles on each side. They also came close to agreeing in principle to scrap all ballistic missiles, a idea that went far beyond the INF proposals and triggered an avalanche of West European complaints that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had gone too far. Although the West Europeans at that point were pressing hard for completion of an INF treaty, the <LOCATION> Reykjavik </LOCATION> talk of eliminating all ballistic missiles caused a serious political crisis in <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>. The Europeans felt they had not been adequately consulted by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration on an issue that directly affected Western <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s security Shortly after that summit, <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, then premier of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, called on the <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> allies to create a new security charter to defend their interests. `` The scope of the proposals put forward by both sides at the <LOCATION> Reykjavik </LOCATION> summit in October seemed to shake the very basis on which our conception of U.S.-Soviet relations is founded,'' <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> said. His remark carried with it the weight of broad agreement among the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> allies that they should insist on playing a bigger political role. `` One can not remain forever a spectator to the American-Soviet negotiations, even if they are positive,'' Prime Minister <PERSON> Filipe </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> told the French mewspaper <ORGANIZATION> Le </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monde </ORGANIZATION> in an interview published Feb. 11. This concern is rooted partly in the allies' belief that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is losing some of its international political predominance and that economic strains induced by years of huge budget deficits may soon force it to pull some American troops out of <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, a feeling has grown in recent years that the Europeans are bearing too small a share of the burden of Western defense. In June 1984 the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, by a 55-41 vote, defeated a proposal to withdraw nearly one-third of the 326,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops based in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> unless the allies did more to improve non-nuclear defenses. This triggered a new effort in <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>, spearheaded by <PERSON> Carrington </PERSON> and former a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Abshire </PERSON>, to cooperate more on defense planning and in the development, production and buying of armaments. A key result of this was the Conventional Defense Improvements initiative approved at a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> defense ministers meeting in May 1985. Talk of strengthening the `` European pillar'' of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> has been around since President <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> coined the term in 1962. But it has taken on added urgency in recent years, partly due to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic problems. A study by political leaders and defense experts from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and eight European <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> countries, published in May, called for a high-level alliance meeting early in 1989 to revise the trans-Atlantic pact on which Western security has rested for 39 years. `` A fundamental change has occurred in the U.S.-European relationship,'' the study concluded. It said the Europeans should take more of the economic and political burdens of alliance leadership, and that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should accustom itself to conducting <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> business on more even terms with the Europeans. As perceptions about the military threat posed by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> have changed in recent years, trans-Atlantic friction has grown over how to respond to security problems outside the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> area. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bombing of <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> in April 1986 brought this conflict to a peak. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> was the only <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> country to explicitly support the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bombing raid, which was described by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> as a defensive response to Libyan backing for terrorist attacks on Americans in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The French and Spanish governments declined to permit <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> F-111 fighter-bombers to cross their airspace en route from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> and back. <PERSON> Carrington </PERSON> says this marked the low point of his four years at <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>. `` It was quite nasty,'' he said. `` It brought to a head the American perception that the Europeans were really not interested in anything that happened outside the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> area.'' It also hardened a West European view of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration as a group of `` cowboys,'' <PERSON> Carrington </PERSON> said. The strains eased over time, helped by the decision of several <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> countries, including <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, to join the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> in mine-clearing operations in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> starting in 1987.
</TEXT>
