<HEAD>Key Dates in Changes within NATO since 1984</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-NATO Changes, b0569-b0570</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are some key dates in affairs of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> since 1984: JUNE 1984 _ Lord <PERSON> Carrington </PERSON> takes over from <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Luns </PERSON> as <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> secretary-general. JANUARY 1985 _ <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gromyko </PERSON> meet in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> and set the agenda for new superpower arms talks, covering medium - and long-range nuclear weapons as well as space and defensive weapons MARCH 1985 _ <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is named general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, and as such the leader of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> defense ministers for the first time formally endorse the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Strategic Defense Initiative, or `` star wars'' plan. MAY 1985 _ Allied defense ministers approve the Conventional Defense Improvements plan for strengthening non-nuclear forces. NOVEMBER 1985 _ President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> meets <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> for the first time in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. JANUARY 1986 _ <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> calls for the global elimination of nuclear weapons by the end of the century. MARCH 1986 _ In a national referendum, Spaniards vote to stay in <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>. It is the first time a member country has considered leaving. MAY 1986 _ <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> foreign ministers, meeting in <LOCATION> Halifax </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nova </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Scotia </LOCATION>, urge `` bold new steps'' in <LOCATION> East-West </LOCATION> negotiations to reduce troops and non-nuclear weaponry throughout <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. OCTOBER 1986 _ <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorabachev </PERSON>, meeting in <LOCATION> Reykjavik </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>, agree in principle to eliminate all medium-range nuclear missiles. JUNE 1987 _ <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> foreign ministers endorse <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s offer to widen the medium-range missile deal to include shorter-range rockets. Later, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Gen. <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>, an opponent of the deal, is dropped as Supreme Allied Commander <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and replaced by Gen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Galvin </PERSON>. DECEMBER 1987 _ <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> sign the missile treaty at their summit in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Manfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON> is chosen to succeed <PERSON> Carrington </PERSON> as <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> secretary general when <PERSON> Carrington </PERSON> leaves in June 1988. MARCH 1988 _ A <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> summit meeting reaffirms the basic principles of the alliance, pledges to modernize <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> nuclear weapons in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and calls for major reductions in non-nuclear forces. JUNE 1988 _ <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, meeting in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, put the medium-range nuclear missile treaty into effect.
</TEXT>
