<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, June 24-26, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Anna Maria Horsford Shapes Thelma on NBC's `Amen'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1 of June 13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Horsford </PERSON> has turned a supporting role as <PERSON> Thelma </PERSON>, the unmarried, 39-year-old deacon's daughter on `` Amen,'' into one of the most popular characters on the <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> hit comedy. <PERSON> Thelma </PERSON>, who's been engaged and jilted 18 times, has been described as a `` vampy virgin.'' <PERSON> Horsford </PERSON> said in an interview that she sees <PERSON> Thelma </PERSON> as a reluctant spinster who, even at 39, is still holding on to her virtue. `` It's always a challenge to a man to be first,'' she said. `` Do n't ever assume that virtuous girls are uninteresting.'' <PERSON> Horsford </PERSON> was born and raised in <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION>, the daughter of a businessman, and attended <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s High School for the Performing Arts. She said she began to draw up a history for <PERSON> Thelma </PERSON> as soon as she was cast. `` She's unemployed, unmarried and living at home with her father -LRB- played by <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON> <PERSON> Hemsley </PERSON> -RRB-,'' she said. `` I wrote it all down. Then I could see what's my attitude toward someone like that. My first reaction was that she was spoiled by her father. She does n't do what she does n't have to do `` I looked for her endearing qualities, too. She'd been engaged many times, so I looked back in my past at the girls who got the ring but never got to the altar. I created a woman who is quiet, strong, manipulative and secure in the sense that her life has been consistent since childhood.'' If Daddy spoils her, it's the handsome Rev. <PERSON> Reuben </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON>, played by <PERSON> Clifton </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, who puts her in a matrimonial mood. So far, her love is unrequited. Before `` Amen,'' <PERSON> Horsford </PERSON> worked regularly in films, including `` St. Elmo's Fire,'' `` Heartburn,'' `` Class,'' `` Crackers,'' `` The Fan'' and `` Street Smart,'' plus in a number of television movies. `` I've played a lot of strong women in films,'' she said. `` Sometimes I've been a policewoman and carried a gun. But I really hate guns and abhor screen violence. My father was shot by a holdup man when I was 4, and thereafter he wore a gun to work. I never dated in high school. All the boys knew <PERSON> Daddy </PERSON> carried a gun.'' She said in her screen roles she has tried to portray strength through her presence. `` I think a character who can scare you with his presence is much stronger than a person who needs a gun,'' she said. `` I try to show that in my acting.'' Because of the regularity of her work in movies, she said she was n't terribly worried about whether she would land the role in the network series. She had tested for the role in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, then was called to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> to test opposite <PERSON> Hemsley </PERSON>. `` I came out on a Sunday, auditioned on Monday and was told there'd probably be a decision on Tuesday. Well, there was no word on Tuesday. Or Wednesday or Thursday. By then I was back in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. My agent called me at noon Friday and said, ` Guess what? You have the job.''' <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> had made a reservation for her on a 4 p.m. plane that day. `` I said, ` Oh, no, is this the way <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> does it?' I flew back to <LOCATION> L.A. </LOCATION> and went to work the next day.'' <PERSON> Horsford </PERSON> said she has learned that in television you have to come out ready, with all your lines memorized. `` I said I'm so grateful for every lesson, for every showcase I've done,'' she said. `` You do a sitcom and you can use everything you've learned. You do n't have time to think of criticism because it's so fast. I think what makes a hit show is an actor giving a lot of his or her resource to a writer. `` A producer hires you hoping that you can deliver. But there's no way a producer can anticipate how the audience will respond to you The writers pick up little pieces of you and your personality and put it into the script. An actor's heartache is having a great line but then losing it because it did n't work in rehearsal. In television, if something does n't work the first time there's no second chance.'' When she moved to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> two years ago to start work on `` Amen,'' she found herself facing another problem. She had to learn to drive. `` I'm an expert now,'' she said. `` I went to driving school for seven weeks. When I first came here I got very friendly with everyone at <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION>. You get humble and ask everybody for a ride. I still have a soft spot in my heart, too, for all the men who let me drive and sat in the passenger seat while I was learning.''
</TEXT>
