<TEXT>
 `` Wall Street'' -LRB- CBS-Fox, VHS-Beta: $ 89.98, Rated R -RRB- When `` Wall Street'' hit movie theaters last year, the real street was crashing and high-rolling traders such as <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> were being marched to prison. Anyone who thinks this movie offers any real insight into the quirks and greed that make stock market life so enticing will be disappointed. One of the many implausible aspects of this film written and directed by <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Stone </PERSON> is that there is n't a single decent woman's role. It could be that the film is implicitly blaming testosterone for Wall Street's vices. But who cares? This movie is great silly fun, fueled by superb acting from Oscar winner <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>, father and son <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hal </PERSON> <PERSON> Holbrook </PERSON> and <PERSON> Terrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Stamp </PERSON>. There's even a terrific walk-on by <PERSON> Sylvia </PERSON> <PERSON> Miles </PERSON> as a pushy East Side real estate saleswoman. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> is suitably sinister as <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Gekko </PERSON>, Wall Street dealmaker, dream-weaver and crusher of innocent companies. The younger <PERSON> Sheen </PERSON> plays <PERSON> Bud </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>, a young <PERSON> Sammy </PERSON> <PERSON> Glick-type </PERSON> broker who sees <PERSON> Gekko </PERSON> as his ticket to the big bucks. He will do anything to get into <PERSON> Gekko </PERSON>'s empire of beautiful women, limousines, cocaine and mega-deals. While at <PERSON> Gekko </PERSON>'s beach house he meets a beautiful but vacuous interior decorator played -LRB- <PERSON> Darryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Hannah </PERSON> -RRB- who has big money dreams of her own. <ORGANIZATION> Fidelity </ORGANIZATION>, it turns out, is not her strong suit _ nor are brains. <PERSON> Gekko </PERSON> spins out such wisdom as `` greed is good,'' and `` every battle is won before it is fought.'' <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> ingratiates himself to <PERSON> Gekko </PERSON> by becoming a corporate spy and feeding him insider information. But when he finds himself embroiled in a take-over scheme that threatens to break up the airline for which his father works, this proves too much even for the avaricious young <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>. _ By <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitgang </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
