<HEAD>In the Groove: Dylan Reviewed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
. `` Down in the Groove'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dylan </PERSON> <PERSON> Columbia </PERSON> proclaims on the packaging of <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dylan </PERSON>'s latest album that he is a `` 1988 Rock & amp; Roll Hall of Fame Inductee.'' Did they think someone out there would pick up the record and say, `` I never heard of this guy, but look, he's in the Rock' n' Roll Hall of Fame How bad can he be?'' Most anyone browsing in the <PERSON> Dylan </PERSON> section is going to be aware that his most recent `` Knocked Out Loaded'' was pretty mediocre and that even the darkly brilliant `` Empire Burlesque'' that preceded it was an acquired taste. <PERSON> Dylan </PERSON> needs a strong, accessible back-to-basics record. `` Down in the Groove'' is it _ with an asterisk. <PERSON> Dylan </PERSON> wrote only four of the 10 songs, two of which were co-written with the Grateful Dead's <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>. The Dylan songs are superb, and covers suit him so well, they might as well be his. The record is so strong because he has n't insisted on filling it with his own material, however weak. Instead, he offers unique Dylanesque treatments of standards including, believe it or not, `` Shenandoah.'' He's also backed by an all-star lineup of pals, including <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Clapton </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Knopfler </PERSON>, the Grateful Dead, <ORGANIZATION> Full </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simonon </PERSON> of The Clash, <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> of the Sex Pistols, <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> and Clydie and <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>. Perhaps the best cut on the album is `` Silvio,'' one of the Dylan-Hunter collaborations, with <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Weir </PERSON> and Brent Mydland singing backup. The other Dylan-Hunter tune, `` Ugliest Girl in the World,'' shows our man's sense of humor intact: `` The woman I love, she got ta hook in her nose, her eyebrows meet and she wears second-hand clothes, she speaks with a stutter and she walks with a hop, I do n't know why I love her, but I just ca n't stop.'' `` Had a Dream About You Baby'' is fine hard rock, one of two original songs <PERSON> Dylan </PERSON> wrote for his movie, `` Hearts of Fire,'' which has not been released, though the soundtrack album is available. `` Down in the Groove'' opens with <PERSON> Wilbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>'s `` Let's Stick Together. `` When Did You Leave Heaven'' is a crooner's number, and <PERSON> Dylan </PERSON>'s strained wail is downright charming `` Death Is Not the End'' is the other <PERSON> Dylan </PERSON> original, gospel tinged with a <ORGANIZATION> Celtic </ORGANIZATION> dirge. He closes with the <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION>' haunting ballad of alienation, `` Rank Strangers to Me'': `` I wandered again to my home in the mountains, where in youth's early dawn I was happy and free. I looked for my friends, but I never could find them. I found they were all rank strangers to me.''
