<HEAD>Richmond Station's Lasers, Telescopes Guide the World</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From an abandoned blimp base, scientists are peering beyond the stars and studying how the earth moves. Their work guides ships at sea, satellites in space and even a cab driver in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, and could someday help predict earthquakes. They also found that the generally stable <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> area is rising a fraction of an inch a year. On the grounds of the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Naval Observatory's <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> station south of here are optical and radio telescopes, a visiting German laser system and soon a gravity meter, all designed to pinpoint locations and distances. `` We're observing continental drift, changes in the earth's crust and movements along fault lines, as well as the earth's spin and wobble,'' says <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> Babcock </PERSON>, one of 10 civilians at the station and its director `` As far as I know, this network is the only source of such measurements.'' The station, which costs less than $ 500,000 a year to run, is part of a <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> network used by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and other satellite-launching nations to program guidance systems and pinpoint locations. The data is being fed into a growing worldwide satellite network that will become the definitive source for navigators. It is not only available to ships, planes, satellites and submarines, but to motorists via computerized maps. `` I met a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> taxi driver who had a receiver mounted in his cab _ he said it was quicker and more accurate than using a map,'' says Ms. <PERSON> Babcock </PERSON>. There are even hand-held receivers can pinpoint location and headings for hikers, explorers and rescue teams. <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, set up in 1949 at a World War II blimp base, also has the only backup to the Master Clock at the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Observatory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, a basis for accurate time measurement all over the world. The cesium-fueled clocks at <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, which measure time by the radioactive element's rate of decay, are checked constantly against those in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to prevent errors. The exact time is shared with other points by bouncing the information off satellites. Even at the speed of light, phone lines are useless for comparing the readings because switching stations can slow the signals. However most of the staff's time is spent looking upward. The 60-foot diameter radiotelescope seeks out quasars, small sources of intense radio emissions billions of light-years away at the edge of the visible universe. `` If one of them seems to be moving, we know it's really the earth that's wobbling,'' says Ms. <PERSON> Babcock </PERSON>. The measurements are constantly checked and rechecked to see how the earth and points on its surface are changing. In addition, researchers from the Wettzell Station in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> are using a mobile laser telescope to fire green light beams at a two-foot orbiting LAGEOS satellite covered with 40 four-inch mirrors. The beam bounces 3,500 miles back to show up on a screen in a trailer crammed with electronic equipment. `` You can do a lot of things with this information. It's a very accurate position fix for a satellite, or for points on earth,'' says German scientist <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Etling </PERSON>. Distances over 1,000 miles can be calculated to within an inch or two using this method, he says. The Richmond scientists plan to install by year's end a gravity meter, a metal ball suspended in a magnetic field that can measure minute changes in mass below it. And Ms. <PERSON> Babcock </PERSON> hopes to install a laser system that can bounce beams off mirrors left on the lunar surface by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet moonwalkers. The new systems may eventually have to replace the observatory's optical telescope, which will become as useless as <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s when encroaching development lights up the night skies and makes stargazing Ms. <PERSON> Babcock </PERSON> has no doubt ever more exotic measuring sticks will be available. `` In this field, the technology is changing so fast we never really get to a standard system.''
</TEXT>
