<HEAD>Chiropractic Struggles For Credibility Despite Court Victory</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> CHICAGO </LOCATION> _ Those who have found relief through chiropractors' spinal manipulation sing its praises, and physicians are reluctant to criticize after the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> lost an antitrust lawsuit, but chiropractic is still struggling for credibility `` We still meet lots of prejudices and unfair treatment,'' says <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON>, past director of the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiropractic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` I see a lot of patients that deal with chiropractors, and generally they are not accepted very well by the general medical community, but they do help a lot of people,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Robbins </PERSON>, a neurologist specializing in headache treatments in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Northbrook </LOCATION>. The number of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> chiropractors grew from 13,000 in 1970 to more than 30,000 in 1985, the last year for which figures are available. Chiropractors differ from physicians in that they perform no surgery and prescribe no drugs, preferring to let the body heal itself after full nerve function is restored. Chiropractic, derived from the Greek for `` effective hand,'' is based on the theory that disease may be caused by interference with nerve function, which practitioners try to correct by manipulating the spine and joints. There are now 15 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> chiropractic colleges accredited by the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiropractic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>. Students must complete 4,200 classroom hours of medical education over four years, similar to medical school. The curriculum includes anatomy, physiology, nutrition, pathology, public health, clinical and laboratory diagnosis, gynecology, obstetrics, pediatrics, X-ray technique and interpretation, geriatrics, psychology and ethics. Far from the stereotype of the medical school dropout, chiropractic students are more typically people who have already established credentials in nursing, physical therapy, teaching and dentistry, said Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON>, vice president for academic affairs at <ORGANIZATION> Logan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiropractic </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>. `` Twenty-two percent of students have master's degrees or better.'' Chiropractic now is seeking credibility through scientific proof of its effectiveness, said <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolk </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiropractic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va </LOCATION>. The foundation has earmarked $ 5 million over the next six years for independent research.
</TEXT>
