 From an abandoned blimp base, scientists are peering beyond the stars and studying how the earth moves. Their work guides ships at sea, satellites in space and even a cab driver in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, and could someday help predict earthquakes. They also found that the generally stable <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> area is rising a fraction of an inch a year. On the grounds of the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Naval Observatory's <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> station south of here are optical and radio telescopes, a visiting German laser system and soon a gravity meter, all designed to pinpoint locations and distances. `` We're observing continental drift, changes in the earth's crust and movements along fault lines, as well as the earth's spin and wobble,'' says <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> Babcock </PERSON>, one of 10 civilians at the station and its director `` As far as I know, this network is the only source of such measurements.'' The station, which costs less than $ 500,000 a year to run, is part of a <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> network used by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and other satellite-launching nations to program guidance systems and pinpoint locations. The data is being fed into a growing worldwide satellite network that will become the definitive source for navigators. It is not only available to ships, planes, satellites and submarines, but to motorists via computerized maps and to hikers, explorers and rescue teams via hand-held receivers. <PERSON> Richmond </PERSON> also has the only backup to the Master Clock at the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Observatory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, a basis for accurate time measurement all over the world. The clocks at <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, which measure time by the rate of decay of cesium, are checked constantly against those in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>.
