<SECOND>PM-Video Yearbooks,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yearbooks Now Filmed Instead of Printed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY STERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Still pictures and written words may capture high school and college graduates' best memories but a video yearbook is what's needed to really go beyond the sounds of silence, students and industry executives say. `` There are a number of pitches we use,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Levitan </PERSON>, president of <LOCATION> Durham </LOCATION>, N.C.-based Yearbook Enterprises. `` It brings those black and white photos to life by capturing the excitement and emotion that a print yearbook ca n't always do.'' <PERSON> Levitan </PERSON> said his company, like others in the field, do n't try to undercut sales of the traditional yearbook but offer the video as a supplement. Videos cost between $ 20 and $ 40 depending on their length, which can range from 30 minutes to 90 minutes. A yearbook, which must go to print midway through the second half of the school year, can not always include things like senior prom and graduation. <ORGANIZATION> Yearbook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> works with about 50 colleges and high schools in teaching students how to use video equipment and buying the rights to songs that young filmmakers want to use as background music. `` It's educational,'' said <PERSON> Levitan </PERSON>, who filmed <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s yearbook for two years before graduating in 1983 `` Students grew up watching <ORGANIZATION> MTV </ORGANIZATION>. This is an opportunity to create with video. They're creating their own MTV.'' One student attracted by the idea was <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Zager </PERSON>, an 18-year-old senior at <LOCATION> Lawrenceville </LOCATION> Prep. He has coordinated filming and sales of his school's video yearbook, which sells for $ 39.95, for the past two years. He said sales expanded this year because more students became aware of a video's knack to recapture the feeling of student plays and homecoming football games. `` There's something about sitting down and watching events in color,'' said <PERSON> Zager </PERSON>, of <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON>. `` It gives you an honest sense of the school.'' <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION> junior <PERSON> Caroline </PERSON> <PERSON> Havens </PERSON>, who worked on her school's 30-minute video, agreed `` This is a more living type of yearbook,'' said the 20-year junior from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION> `` We do n't try to downplay -LRB- traditional -RRB- yearbooks but this is a lot more lively.'' The video yearbook companies take different approaches. At Campus Camera, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> company co-founded by two former cameramen from an <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> television station, the philosophy is `` leave the filmmaking to us.'' `` Our quality of equipment is equivalent to a TV station,'' co-owner <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pashuck </PERSON> said. `` I would n't hand that over to a student.'' <PERSON> Pashuck </PERSON> said students also might tend to only film their friends. Outside cameramen prevent that and guarantee a quality product. And <PERSON> Pashuck </PERSON> and his partner have enjoyed their first year with the two schools _ <ORGANIZATION> Mainland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Linwood </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Mater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Middletown </LOCATION> _ that they've worked with. <PERSON> Pashuck </PERSON> said Campus Camera, like other video yearbook enterprises, will grow in the years ahead by capitalizing on people's expanding familiarity with video equipment. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, the 30-year-old head of Dallas-based <ORGANIZ