<HEAD>For Ashland Oil, 1988 Has Been Good and Bad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASHLAND, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, 1988 has been one public relations disaster after another. First there was an oil spill. Then there were complaints about pollution. Now a federal trial has gone against it. It all started Jan. 2 when a 4-million-gallon storage tank collapsed near <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, sending more than 700,000 gallons of diesel fuel into the <LOCATION> Monongahela </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> rivers in one of the worst inland oil spills in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history. Two weeks later, the company was fined $ 95,000 for violating air pollution standards at its <LOCATION> Catlettsburg </LOCATION> refinery. State air quality officials received 80 complaints from nearby residents during three weeks in February and March. In mid-March, a report by the <ORGANIZATION> federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> had violated regulations at its hazardous-waste dump near the refinery. But perhaps the biggest public relations problem of all hit Friday, when a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> jury in <LOCATION> Covington </LOCATION> ruled that the company engaged in racketeering in 1980 when it made payments to foreign government officials to obtain crude oil. The jury awarded nearly $ 70 million to former vice presidents <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, who said they had been fired for refusing to take part in the payments and for telling <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government agencies about the money. <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION>, which is <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>'s largest corporation and the nation's largest independent oil refiner, said it would appeal. Whether the awards are whittled down by higher courts remains to be seen, but the company expects any payment to be covered by a $ 75 million policy with <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Money aside, however, observers say <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> has an image problem `` The public perception is that something must be wrong if it -LRB- the case -RRB- has gone this far,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lad </PERSON>, an assistant professor of management at <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said some lawyers following the case figured <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> would win by persuading jurors its past business practices were commonplace. <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON> said the jury's decision may reflect some anger among consumers. `` There is the feeling that big business _ the Fortune 500 companies _ have gotten away with murder,'' he said. A public explanation might improve <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION>'s image, suggested <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyers </PERSON>, former chairman of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and author of `` When It Hits the Fan,'' a book on corporate crises. `` The way to lose in the court of public opinion is to hide behind your lawyers,'' <PERSON> Meyers </PERSON> said. He said the burden of repairing the company's public image rests with its current chairman, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>. `` Nobody is as believable as the chief executive officer,'' <PERSON> Meyers </PERSON> said. That's a notion Hall reinforced in January, when he drew national praise for publicly discussing the massive oil spill. <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON> said Saturday that he thinks Hall will make a statement, although it wo n't come until the company files legal motions related to Friday's decision. <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> has 10 days to do so. <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON> said the public relations problems have masked an otherwise good financial year for the company. In the six months that ended March 31, <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> earned $ 67 million, not including a one-time gain of $ 31 million, compared with $ 22 million a year earlier. Revenue also rose, to $ 3.9 billion from $ 3.2 billion in 1987. `` If you really want to know how the year has been for the company, it has been very good,'' <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON> said. `` I think the shareholders are pleased by the performance of the company. <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> has interests in petroleum, coal, chemicals and construction.
