<HEAD>Foreign Ministers Approve Joint Declaration With East Bloc</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIPPE NEURAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUXEMBOURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign ministers of the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> on Monday approved an accord establishing formal relations with the Soviet-led Council for Mutual Economic Assistance, or Comecon. The agreement was initialled by <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Comecon </ORGANIZATION> officials last week in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. It is to be put into force at an official signing ceremony in <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION> on June 25. The pact sets the stage for exchanges of information but does n't establish bilateral trade relations It marks the Communist bloc's first official recognition of the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> since the Common Market was created 31 years ago. For years, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and its Communist allies virtually ignored the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>, calling it a quasi-military extension of the American-led <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> alliance. The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Comecon </ORGANIZATION> have been negotiating the terms of a joint declaration on mutual recognition since September 1985. <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> member nations include: <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s partners in <ORGANIZATION> Comecon </ORGANIZATION> are <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION>. Trade between <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Comecon </ORGANIZATION> members totaled about $ 50 billion last year, about half of which was between the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, according to the June issue of <ORGANIZATION> East-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publications </ORGANIZATION>, a Brussels-based newsletter. The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> has sought to emphasize bilateral contacts with the <ORGANIZATION> Comecon </ORGANIZATION> member countries rather than bloc-to-bloc relations. This is mainly because the Common Market says <ORGANIZATION> Comecon </ORGANIZATION> does not have equivalent authority to decide trade and other issues for its members. Last week, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> submitted formal requests to open their own bilateral diplomatic relations with the EEC. The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> hopes to wrap up a bilateral trade and cooperation agreement with <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> this year. During their <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION> meeting, the foreign ministers gave the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> negotiators new instructions for the <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> talks.
