<HEAD>OPEC Ministers Meet Informally To Discuss Production Quota</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBs 2nd graf pvs, The Organization ..., with one graf to
delete erroneous reference reference to proposed new limit. A
version moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> ministers today met informally to discuss whether to change their existing oil production quota, amid speculation that the talks have stalled. The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries on Sunday adjourned its regular midyear conference to allow the 13-nation cartel's oil ministers to informally discuss disagreements. The conference began Saturday and will resume Tuesday. The ministers have been considering whether to change an existing agreement among 12 of the members that limits their oil production to 15.06 million barrels a day. That quota, which was extended in December and expires June 30, was aimed at supporting oil prices at $ 18 a barrel. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has refused to sign the agreement because it wants an output quota equal to that of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, at war with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> since September 1980, was granted a quota of 1.54 million barrels a day in a previous agreement. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s daily quota is 2.369 million barrels. Some <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members want to cut production to push oil prices up, while others want to increase output or at least hold it steady to take advantage of an expected increase in demand later this year. But analysts believe <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> is so deeply divided it will extend the existing agreement for at least three months. `` We are working on compromise,'' <LOCATION> Indonesian </LOCATION> oil minister <PERSON> Ginandjar </PERSON> <PERSON> Kartasasmita </PERSON> said today. `` There are agreements on most of the issues.'' He said he strongly believed the cartel would make a decision either Tuesday or Wednesday. `` There will definitely be an agreement,'' added Saudi Arabian oil minister <PERSON> Hisham </PERSON> <PERSON> Nazer </PERSON>. But ministerial sources from two countries also said Sunday that the cartel _ expecting a stalemate _ was most likely to extend the current production quota. `` There's a degree of disappointment and confusion,'' said <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON>, an oil analyst at the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd </ORGANIZATION>. Adding to the confusion was the departure of two Arab oil ministers, with one expected to return by Tuesday but the other saying he might not. <PERSON> Mana </PERSON> <PERSON> Saeed </PERSON> <PERSON> Oteiba </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION>' oil minister, said Sunday he was returning to his country for consultations with his government and that he might or might not return. He gave no reason for his sudden departure. Kuwaiti Oil Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalifa </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON> will leave today, but will return in time for the Tuesday session, members of his delegation said. Observers speculated that <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON> was going to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to appear before the British government's <ORGANIZATION> Monopolies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mergers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> about <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s purchase of more than 20 percent of <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> earlier this year. `` The fact that <PERSON> Oteiba </PERSON> must consult with his supeiors is very reminiscent of a stall. It's awfully convenient, is n't it?'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Gignoux </PERSON>, managing director of the <ORGANIZATION> international </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> department </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. Oil markets were disappointing today, with the spot price of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> Brent Blend, the most widely traded international crude oil, falling to 55 cents to $ 15.30 a barrel and then held steady on the spot market. The 13 members of the cartel are <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Gabon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Qatar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>.
