<HEAD>Court Lets Stand Ruling On Federal Home Loan Bank Bonds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today let stand a ruling that states indirectly may tax interest paid to financial institutions from investments in <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> bonds. The court, citing the lack of a `` substantial federal question,'' rejected a challenge to a <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> bank franchise tax. The <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> challenged the tax, seeking a refund of $ 197,310 it paid under protest to the state for the years 1979 through 1982. During that period, the bank reported $ 2.82 million in interest from <ORGANIZATION> FHLB </ORGANIZATION> bonds. The sum was included in the bank's net earnings that were subject to <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>'s franchise tax, which is imposed on financial institutions for the privilege of doing business in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>. The difficulty over whether earnings from <ORGANIZATION> FHLB </ORGANIZATION> bonds are taxable arises because of two apparently conflicting federal laws. A 1932 law that created the <ORGANIZATION> FHLB </ORGANIZATION> generally exempts the bonds from taxes. But a law enacted in 1862 permits states to levy a `` non-discriminatory franchise tax'' on `` stocks and obligations of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> government'' that generally are exempt from state and local taxes. The <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upheld the state franchise tax, ruling in October that the 1862 law takes precedence. The state court based its ruling in part on a 1975 opinion by the general counsel's office of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. The state court said a franchise tax paid for the privilege of doing business in the state is not the same as a direct tax on a bank's income. The state court also said the tax does not violate the Constitution's Supremacy Clause, which binds states to adhere to federal law. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> vs. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assessments </ORGANIZATION>, 87-1080.
