<HEAD>Justices Rule in Kentucky Lawyer-Ad Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 8 grafs detail; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today barred states from banning all direct mail advertisements sent by lawyers to potential clients. The court, by a 6-3 vote, ruled in a <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> case that states violate free-speech rights when they prohibit lawyers from soliciting business by sending truthful and nondeceptive letters to people they know face particular legal problems. Writing for the court, Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said states may require lawyers to file copies of such soliciting letters with a state agency authorized to penalize actual abuses. But <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said the potential for abuse does not justify a total ban, as imposed in <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>. `` Our recent decisions involving commercial speech have been grounded in the faith that the free flow of commercial information is valuable enough to justify imposing on would-be regulators the costs of distinguishing the truthful from the false, the helpful from the misleading and the harmless from the harmful,'' <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said. He was joined by Justices <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. The three dissenters _ Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> and Justices <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> and <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> _ said it was time to overturn the 1977 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision that first overturned the legal profession's longtime ban on any type of lawyer advertising. `` Rather than continuing to work out all the consequences of -LRB- the 1977 ruling's approach -RRB- we should now return to the states the legislative function that has so inappropriately been taken from them in the context of attorney advertising,'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> wrote for the three. The court's 1977 decision said a total ban on lawyer advertising violates free-speech rights. Like other commercial speech, however, lawyer ads are constitutionally protected only when truthful and nondeceptive. The court in 1978 expressly prohibited lawyers from seeking business through in-person solicitation of people known to have legal problems. But today, the court said that in some cases solicitation through direct mailings must be allowed. `` Admittedly, a letter that is personalized to the recipient presents an increased risk of deception, intentional or inadvertent,'' <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said. `` But merely because targeted, direct-mail solicitation presents lawyers with opportunities for isolated abuses or mistakes does not justify a total ban on that mode of protected commercial speech,'' he added. <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>'s total ban, fashioned by the state's <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, follows the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> model rule that direct-mail solicitation be banned `` when a significant motive for the lawyer's doing so is the lawyer's pecuniary gain. The <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> model, now declared constitutionally unsound, has been adopted by <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>. Three states _ <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> _ adopted direct-mail bans more restrictive than the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> model. They also now are likely to fall in the face of a free-speech challenge. In <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, the ban on targeted direct-mail ads was challenged by <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapero </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION> lawyer. <PERSON> Shapero </PERSON> had wanted to send a letter to potential clients against whom foreclosure lawsuits had been filed, but he was told that mailing such a solicitation would violate the state lawyer-ethics rules. <PERSON> Shapero </PERSON>'s case now returns to the <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> for further study. The case is <PERSON> Shapero </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, 87-l6.
</TEXT>
