<FIRST>u f PM-Scotus-Securities 2ndLd-Writethru f0063 06-13 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Securities, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0063,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court Allows Bank Subsidiaries To Deal In Some Securities</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS one graf after penultimate graf bgng ``But we are ...
'' to update with American Bankers Association comment; Also moved
on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today allowed banks to use subsidiaries to engage in underwriting and dealing in some securities. The court, over two dissenting votes, let stand a ruling that such activity does not violate a 1933 law aimed primarily at protecting the financial stability of banks by restricting them from speculating in stocks and bonds. Justices <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> voted to hear arguments in the case, but four votes are needed to grant such review. The 1933 federal law, the Glass-Steagall Act, was passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in the wake of the stock market crash of 1929. The law placed various restrictions on banks, in large measure to protect deposits from being squandered on Wall Street. In recent years, the wall of separation between commercial and investment bank activities has been lowered. At issue in the case acted on today were rulings by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> allowing some of the nation's leading banks to use subsidiaries to underwrite and deal in municipal revenue bonds, mortgage-related securities and commercial paper. The latter is a form of IOU used by corporations to finance short-term debt. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> last year said bank subsidiaries may underwrite and deal in such securities as long as they do not exceed 5 to 10 percent of the subsidary's gross revenue. The board said that is in line with the Glass-Stegall Act's requirement that banks may not affiliate with an organization `` engaged principally'' in underwriting or dealing in securities The board's rulings were challenged by the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a trade group of underwriters, brokers andd securities dealers. The 2nd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in February upheld the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> decisions, and the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration urged the justices to leave intact the appeals court rulng. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers said the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> acted properly, and that any change in banking regulations should be left to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The government noted that a moratorium <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> imposed on the type of banking activities involved in the dispute expired in March, and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has not renewed it. Moreover, legislation is pending to repeal parts of the Glass-Steagall Act. Reacting to today's decision, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` We are disappointed the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decided not to hear our appeal to prevent banks, through affiliates, from engaging in a wide range of securities.'' `` But we are pleased the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> itself has erected a series of firewalls ... to prevent banks from taking excessive risks within the securities arena which would further weaken banks and thus endanger the nation's economy,'' <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Pistor </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` This is another hole in the anti-competitive Glass-Steagall Act and another important victory for consumers. But, before large numbers of bank customers will benefit, we need to repeal the Glass-Steagall Act and allow all banks to offer securities services.'' The case is <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION>, 87-1513.
</TEXT>
