 The stock market eased slightly today after seesawing in a narrow range. Analysts noted that traders are reluctant to take on large positions ahead of Tuesday's release of merchandise trade figures for April. The trade report is the first in a flurry of economic indicators due to be released this week that should shed a strong light on the state of the economy. `` There is a feeling of optimism ... that the numbers will paint a picture that the economy is slowing from the breakneck inflationary pace of the first three months, and that's what the market needs,'' noted <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, senior vice president at <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Albany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. That optimism was reflected in the ability of the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials to hover around the 2,100 level `` The most revealing thing about this market is that ... we ca n't drive it down,'' noted <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Seagle </PERSON>, vice president and director of technical research at <ORGANIZATION> Gruntal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` The ability of the Dow to hug the 2,100 level is a signal that this market has started some kind of a summer rally,'' he said. The Dow started the week about eight points shy of its post-crash high, and traders began the session by cashing in on the previous weeks' gains. The Dow had been off about 10 points before turning upward and then seesawing throughout the rest of the session. Institutional investors, mutual funds and foreign buyers are sitting on the sidelines with plenty of cash, and their decisions about whether to re-enter the market could hinge on the upcoming economic data. Among the reports to be issued this week are retail sales, industrial production, business inventories, factory capacity and housing starts.
