<HEAD>Drug Industry Reacts to Supreme Courts' Vaccine Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MORAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling Monday on vaccine liability likely affects only a small group of pharmaceutical manufacturers, but may substantially change how the government approves future inoculations, industry analysts said. The nation's high court said those harmed by a vaccine can sue the government agencies that approved its use. `` This is very good for the vaccine companies, but there are not that many of them,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Vieter </PERSON>, a drug industry analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` One might look ahead to vaccines such as AIDS vaccines and other bio-tech applications, though. `` It seems the government will have to exert quite a bit more care in the approval process to prevent placing the government in a liability situation,'' <PERSON> Vieter </PERSON> said. The court, in a 9-0 vote, reinstated a suit by the parents of a <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> boy who contracted polio after receiving a dose of a federally approved vaccine manufactured by <ORGANIZATION> Lederle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wayne </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, a subsidiary of American Cyanimid. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Stover </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said the question of whether the government can be held liable for approving drugs and vaccines that eventually harm someone has been hotly debated for years. `` It should be very significant for that part of the industry and <ORGANIZATION> Lederle </ORGANIZATION> in particular,'' he said. <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Homma </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Lederle </ORGANIZATION>, said the company's top executives and legal department want to study the decision before issuing a comment. <ORGANIZATION> Lederle </ORGANIZATION> shares the majority of the vaccine production business in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Merck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Rahway </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION>' Wyeth Division of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a Canadian company. Officials from <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Merck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> also declined to comment, though one <ORGANIZATION> Merck </ORGANIZATION> executive said `` it's about time'' the government is held accountable for the approval process. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Grayson </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceutical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said the group's legal department also wants to study the decision before any statement is made <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers argued before the court that if such damage suits are allowed, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, which currently tests and licenses vaccines, may be forced into the business of insuring them, jeopardizing the entire drug-approval process. The polio vaccine Orimun, a form of <PERSON> Sabin </PERSON> oral vaccine, was administered to 3-month-old <PERSON> Kevan </PERSON> <PERSON> Berkovitz </PERSON> in 1979. Three months later, the child contracted polio and is now paralyzed, partially deformed and can breathe only with the help of a machine. The vaccine was approved by the federal government in 1963. The <PERSON> Berkovitz </PERSON>'s suit was rejected by the 3rd <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> in 1987.
