<HEAD>Dollar Slightly Higher; Gold Rises After Falling in Europe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar rose slightly Monday, but brokers said trading was extremely quiet prior to the release of monthly <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures and the <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> economic summit. Gold prices also advanced slightly in restrained <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trading after falling more than $ 7 an ounce in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted gold at $ 449.70 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from $ 449 late Friday. Foreign-exchange dealers attributed the sluggish trading partly to their own reluctance to speculate about the dollar's movement prior to the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s report on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit for April, due Tuesday morning. The trade numbers are a powerful influence on the dollar because they have become the most visible symbol of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' unrelenting appetite for imports, a sensitive political and economic issue The nation's deficit shrank to a three-year low of $ 9.7 billion in March, surprising many traders and giving the dollar a substantial boost. But some fear the March number was grossly low and the April deficit could therefore be unexpectedly high, despite a strengthening of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports in recent months. Estimates on the April deficit ranged from below $ 9 billion to above $ 14.5 billion. `` Each number has exasperated traders because it is so unpredictable,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Watson </PERSON>, vice president and chief corporate dealer in <ORGANIZATION> Swiss </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> office. `` But last month's numbers were so good that the chances of a surprise seem sort of big.'' <PERSON> Varick </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, vice president of foreign exchange at <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Switzerland </ORGANIZATION>'s office in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said another big restraint on trading is the summit of leaders of seven industrialized democracies, starting Sunday in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>. `` I ca n't expect anything to happen -LRB- to the dollar -RRB-, even with the trade numbers, until the <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> summit is over,'' he said. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar closed at 125.19 Japanese yen, up slightly from 124.85 yen late Friday. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar was quoted at 125.10 yen. By the time trading concluded in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the dollar was worth 125.12 yen, higher than its 124.88 yen on Friday. The British pound fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to $ 1.8165 from $ 1.8175 late Friday. Later in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the pound was quoted at $ 1.8165, cheaper than $ 1.8178 late Friday. Other late-dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Friday, included: 1.7227 West German marks, up from 1.7211; 1.4407 Swiss francs, up from 1.4391; 1.2207 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2199; 5.8195 French francs, up from 5.8135; and 1,280.25 Italian lire, up from 1,278.88. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Friday, included: 1.7241 West German marks, up from 1.7180; 1.4424 Swiss francs, up from 1.4355; 5.7265 French francs, down from 5.8040; 1.9345 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9280; 1,281.75 Italian lire, up from 1,278.50; 1.2203 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2191. Gold futures prices rose slightly in <LOCATION> U.