<FIRST>u f AM-HungryMigrants 1stLd-Writethru f0251 06-13 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungry Migrants, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0251,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Work Arrives for Migrants as Strawberries Ripen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT to northwestern sted northeastern.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES E. BEGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of migrant workers are picking strawberries after waiting weeks for crops to ripen and straining the resources of social service agencies who provided them food and shelter. Cool weather slowed the ripening of the strawberry crop, which traditionally is ready for harvest by June 1. Officials said an unusually heavy influx of 20,000 migrant workers, many from <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, have been waiting for the work to begin. Warm weather over the weekend ripened many fields in the northwestern portion of the state, and others are expected to be ready for picking soon. <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> is the nation's second-largest strawberry producer after <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. `` A lot of fields just turned red over the weekend because of the good weather,'' <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Graven </PERSON>, a division field supervisor for the state Employment Division, said Monday. <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Malensky </PERSON>, owner of <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Berry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Processing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Hillsboro </LOCATION>, west of <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, said it was too early to say how many of the migrants would be put to work because picking has n't begun yet in many fields. `` Last year it started with a bang and kept on going. This year it's starting slowly and wo n't get into full flow till this weekend,'' he said. Social service agencies have made repeated appeals for food and blankets for the migrants, who hav been living with as many as 50 others in one room. The <ORGANIZATION> Salvation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, one of several charitable organizations helping feed and clothe the migrants, has distributed more than 277 tons of food and more than $ 100,000 worth of clothing, blankets and items such as soap, detergent and cooking utensils. Once the harvest is in full swing, `` it will considerably decrease the demands upon us,'' said <PERSON> Titus </PERSON> <PERSON> Herman </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Salvation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>. `` I know that many of them still have obligations to contractors and in some cases to farmers for food,'' Titus said of the pickers. `` ... Maybe for the next couple of weeks they still will be technically without any money, but beyond that they will have money and chances are the social services will be able to step out of the situation, maybe not completely but considerably. We're already seeing a decrease in demand.'' The 1987 strawberry crop ripened early, and 20 percent of it was left in the fields because of a picker shortage. Growers complained that pickers were confused over the new immigration law and refused to cross the border. The state still produced a bumper crop of 94 million pounds that sold for a record $ 31.5 million. This year, migrants began arriving as early as April. Some say they mistakenly were told they had to file immigration legalization documents by May 4, the deadline for aliens not involved in agricultural work. The agricultural workers have until Nov. 30 to file the papers. After that, employers who hire illegal migrant workers will face stiff penalties.
</TEXT>
