<HEAD>Denver Accountant Named to Head Kaiser Steel Corp.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANCHO CUCAMONGA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Kaiser </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which is reorganizing under protection of a federal bankruptcy court, said Monday that <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoddard </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> accountant and attorney, has been named to the new position of chief executive. The appointment has been approved by the unsecured creditors of the one-time industrial giant, and has been submitted for approval to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankruptcy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, which is handling <PERSON> Kaiser </PERSON>'s Chapter 11 case <PERSON> Stoddard </PERSON>, 37, managing director of the <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> law firm of <ORGANIZATION> Roath </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Brega </PERSON>, has worked in the past with employee - and retiree-owned companies Under <PERSON> Kaiser </PERSON>'s reorganization plan, retirees would be the biggest stockholder group through two trusts that deal with retirement and medical benefits. <PERSON> Kaiser </PERSON>, which filed for Chapter 11 protection from its creditors in February 1987, moved its headquarters from <LOCATION> Fontana </LOCATION>, site of its closed plant, to nearby <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cucamonga </LOCATION> this month. The reorganization plan before the court calls for <PERSON> Kaiser </PERSON> to develop a 900-acre industrial park on the site of the Fontana plant, and to open a dump for municipal waste at its shuttered <LOCATION> Eagle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> iron ore mine in <LOCATION> Riverside </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Kaiser </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary with idled mines in <LOCATION> Sunnyside </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Raton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, will file a separate reorganization plan.
