<FIRST>d f BC-China-Economy     06-13 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-China-Economy,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Industrial Output to Grow 16 Percent in First Three
Quarters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s industrial output should grow by 16.3 percent during the first three quarters of this year, while the inflation rate could reach 13 percent during that time, according to an official report. The <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Wu </PERSON> <PERSON> Minglu </PERSON>, economist for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>, as saying industrial output will total $ 236 billion in the first nine months of the year. At the end of April, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s industrial output value was 17.9 percent higher than at the same time last year, the fastest growth in two years. The Chinese government has expressed concern about the rapid growth rate and tried to clamp down on credit and the beginning of new construction projects. The high growth rate, led by expansion of light industry, has strained government finances and depleted scarce raw materials needed for key heavy industry projects. In 1987, industrial output rose by 16.5 percent while the gross national product grew by 9.4 percent. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s commodity retail volume was up by 23.1 percent and retail prices rose 10.7 percent in the first quarter of this year, both highs for the past several years. <PERSON> Wu </PERSON> said that as the state moves to end price controls over more commodities, inflation will continue to rise, hitting 12 percent in the second quarter and 13 percent in the third. Chinese economists regard inflation, spurred by rising consumer demand and the removal of price controls on some food products, as the most serious issue confronting the nation's economic reforms.
