<FIRST>u f AM-CigaretteSuit 4thLd-Writethru f0266 06-13 1103</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cigarette Suit, 4th Ld - Writethru, f0266,1130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Finds Against One of Three Tobacco Companies on Warning Issue</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Restores dropped word in 1st graf. Recasts 12th graf ``Edell,
Cipollone's'' to clarify.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NR3,4,7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal court jury for the first time held a cigarette company partly responsible for the death of a smoker, finding Monday that <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> failed to warn the public about the dangers of cigarettes and violated its promise to produce a safe product. The jury awarded $ 400,000 to <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>, whose wife <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> died of lung cancer in 1984, but rejected his claim of a conspiracy among the three tobacco companies that produced the products his wife used. The damage award was based on the jury's finding that <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION> violated its expressed promise to consumers to make a safe product, thus contributing to Mrs. <PERSON> Cippollone </PERSON>'s death. It also found that <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION> failed to warn the public about the dangers of cigarettes, but awarded no damages because it found Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> 80 percent responsible for her death. <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Lorillard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> were exonerated of conspiring to mislead the public about the dangers of smoking. The jury awarded no punitive damages. Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>, who was 58 when she died, smoked <LOCATION> Chesterfield </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> L </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; M cigarettes, both made by <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION>, before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> required the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> surgeon general's health warnings on cigarette packs in 1966. She smoked for 40 years, later using brands made by <ORGANIZATION> Lorillard </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>. `` The tobacco companies have claimed for the last 20 years that they are invincible,'' said <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Darnell </PERSON>, an attorney for <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>. `` This shows they are not ... they are just like any other company.'' <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION> Attorney <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Kearney </PERSON> said he was pleased by the verdict. `` The jury specifically rejected any claims of -LRB- punitive -RRB- damages,'' he said. `` The floodgates have been closed even firmer than they were before.'' <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>'s main attorney, <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Z. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edell </PERSON>, said he was unsure whether the verdict would lead to more tobacco liability suits. `` I think the jury, for whatever reason, did n't like <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>. That's the problem. They never met <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>,'' he said. However, <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohn </PERSON> said he regarded the jury's award of $ 400,000 as `` sympathy,'' and said he would appeal. <PERSON> Edell </PERSON>, <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>'s attorney, said he would ask the judge to overturn the jury's decision that <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION> pay no damages for the suffering of Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>. That money would have gone to her estate, unlike the $ 400,000 that goes to <LOCATION> Cipollone </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>, 64, of <LOCATION> Lakehurst </LOCATION>, said he was glad the trial was over, `` and I'm glad the verdict came out halfway a win.'' `` It was n't 100 percent. I'm glad that we won partial, but it's a start,'' he said Asked if his wife would be happy about the jury's findings, he said: `` I do n't really know. She started the suit, and I told her I'd continue'til the end.'' The jury began deliberations last Tuesday. As the forewoman answered each question from the court clerk, a gasp rose from the courtroom packed with industry lawyers, analysts and reporters. `` This is basically a victory for the defense,'' <PERSON> Cohn </PERSON> said. The tobacco industry, with $ 35 billion in revenue, waged an extensive and expensive defense against the suit, fearing that a loss could unleash a flood of multimillion dollar liability lawsuits. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>'s attorneys had said the case was especially significant because they got permission to introduce numerous secret corporate documents that spoke of a `` gentleman's agreement'' not to do cancer research, of an industry strategy to create `` doubt about the health charge without actually denying it,'' and of a research program designed `` so that results can not harm'' the industry The companies said statements in the documents represented the views of individuals and were taken out of context. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> financial markets were closed when the verdict was returned. One analyst suggested tobacco stocks might suffer early in Tuesday trading but the decision would be considered an industry victory in the long term. `` I consider this a major plus for the cigarette companies. It is a loss but not a major loss,'' said <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaplan </PERSON>, a tobacco industry analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION>. During the four-month trial, <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> charged that <ORGANIZATION> Lorillard </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> misled the public about the dangers of cigarette smoking and contributed to Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>'s death. The companies contended that she knew the risks but chose to smoke anyway. They also argued that smoking is not a proven cause if cancer, and that her type of cancer has n't been linked to cigarettes anyway. To support the suit's contention that <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION> violated its promise to consumers, <PERSON> Edell </PERSON> introduced examples of <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION>'s advertising from the 1950s One said, `` <PERSON> Rosalind </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> says L & amp; M Filters are Just What the Doctor Ordered!'' Another ad said: `` Nose, Throat and Accessory Organs Not Adversely Affected By Smoking Chesterfields.'' Another said: `` Play Safe, Smoke Chesterfields.'' On Wednesday, the jury asked to see a copy of testimony she gave to lawyers the year of her death and trial testimony by an addiction expert who certified Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> was dependent on cigarettes. On Friday, they asked if the 1984 surgeon general's report on smoking and health was in evidence and whether they could see it. It was not, and the judge said they could not. The suit, filed in federal court Aug. 1, 1983, is one of only a dozen or so to go to a jury. Hundreds of others were dismissed or faded away in the face of the overwhelming legal strength of a well-heeled industry. Another hundred are pending, with lawyers in those cases closely watching the <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> trial. <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Durham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, has 3.6 percent of the $ 22-billion-a-year cigarette market. It has a net income of $ 30.7 million on sales of $ 531.9 million and is the nation's sixth largest cigarette maker and manufactures L & amp; M, <LOCATION> Chesterfield </LOCATION>, Lark and Eve. It employs 1,800. <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> is the leading <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cigarette manufacturer with 37.9 percent of the market and makes Marlboro, the nation's top-selling brand. Its parent corporation, which also owns <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, employs 90,000 in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and reported net earnings of $ 1.84 billion on operating revenues of $ 27.7 billion in 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Lorillard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, whose brands include <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> and True, has 8.2 percent of domestic cigarette market with a net income of $ 246.9 million on sales of $ 1.68 billion. It is a wholly owned subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Loews </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which also owns <ORGANIZATION> CNA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Bulova </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Watch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and one quarter of <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. It employs 4,650.
